WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.920
[Amit Varma]: Whenever you learn something new, my advice would be before you learn to do it, learn

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:15.500
[Amit Varma]: how to think about it. I used to be a chess player in my teens, but I left playing serious

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:20.540
[Amit Varma]: chess at 19 because I figured out wisely that I wasn't good enough to make it beyond a

00:00:20.540 --> 00:00:25.380
[Amit Varma]: certain point. Now I'm almost addicted to online chess today. And looking back at the

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:31.560
[Amit Varma]: younger me from 25 years ago, I can see clearly what he did not. The younger me was good at

00:00:31.560 --> 00:00:36.660
[Amit Varma]: tactics and bad at strategy. I could pull off awesome combinations and sacrifices. I

00:00:36.660 --> 00:00:41.820
[Amit Varma]: could see a mate in six, but I didn't have good positional understanding of things like

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:47.220
[Amit Varma]: how to create a little space advantage now. So I'll have a killer edge 40 moves later.

00:00:47.220 --> 00:00:52.420
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, one thing that all great chess prodigies have in common is this sort of positional

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:57.500
[Amit Varma]: understanding related to this. Some people think that the depth of opening theory means

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:02.540
[Amit Varma]: that anyone can mix it up with grandmasters. If they learn enough moves, master the opening

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:07.300
[Amit Varma]: theory. But this is simply not true. You can learn all the moves you want, but there will

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:12.980
[Amit Varma]: always be unfamiliar situations where you have to apply principles instead of remembering

00:01:12.980 --> 00:01:18.760
[Amit Varma]: moves. How well you do that is what impacts how good you are. This is a reason top players

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:24.380
[Amit Varma]: today like Magnus Carlsen will often play slightly offbeat lines against lesser players.

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:30.380
[Amit Varma]: Not because those lines are better, but because they lead to more playable positions. Playable

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:35.380
[Amit Varma]: means you need to apply your own brain to the problem and the better player wins. I

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:40.020
[Amit Varma]: played poker professionally for a few years and the same applies there. The pedagogy for

00:01:40.020 --> 00:01:46.060
[Amit Varma]: many young players who go pro is often a version of Indian rote learning. They'll become part

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:51.220
[Amit Varma]: of stables and they'll be staked and coached by pros who will teach them what to do in

00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:56.740
[Amit Varma]: many common situations. For example, at so many big blinds, this is your shoving range,

00:01:56.740 --> 00:02:01.540
[Amit Varma]: this is your reshove range and so on. They can learn this to an adequate level of granularity

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:07.420
[Amit Varma]: to have an edge against recreational players. But when faced with unusual situations, can

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:12.360
[Amit Varma]: they think on their feet? Can they apply principles, do the math themselves in their minds and

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:17.100
[Amit Varma]: figure out the right answers? I have often found that they can't. They have been taught

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:21.420
[Amit Varma]: how to play the game, but they haven't been taught how to think about it. How you play

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:26.180
[Amit Varma]: chess and how you play poker has a limited impact on the world. Other fields matter far

00:02:26.180 --> 00:02:31.220
[Amit Varma]: more public policy. For example, if you are a framer of public policy, you are dealing

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:36.100
[Amit Varma]: with a world far more complex than what chess players or poker players encounter. That's

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:41.220
[Amit Varma]: all the more reason to have intellectual humility to realize the limits of your knowledge and

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:46.220
[Amit Varma]: especially not to fall back reflexively on a bag of tricks you have been taught that

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:51.860
[Amit Varma]: may work elsewhere, but may not necessarily work here. This takes hard work and deep thought.

00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:56.500
[Amit Varma]: It demands hard work and deep thought because every time you get policy wrong in a country

00:02:56.500 --> 00:03:16.580
[Amit Varma]: like India, millions of people are affected. Welcome to the scene and the unseen. I have

00:03:16.580 --> 00:03:22.220
[Amit Varma]: often done episodes begged around books by authors, but this episode is based on a fantastic

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:27.700
[Amit Varma]: paper written by Shruti Rajgopalan and Alex Tabarrok, premature imitation and India's

00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:33.100
[Amit Varma]: flailing state. Shruti and Alex are not just my friends, but two of my favorite thinkers.

00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:37.660
[Amit Varma]: Shruti has been on the scene and the unseen many, many times helping me sharpen and refine

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:42.740
[Amit Varma]: my thinking about the world. And Alex co-writes Marginal Revolution, which in my opinion is

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:47.260
[Amit Varma]: the best blog of all time period. I've been honored to have Alex on my show before, but

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:51.740
[Amit Varma]: that was in the early days when episodes were only 20 minutes long. If you can imagine such

00:03:51.740 --> 00:03:56.620
[Amit Varma]: a pitiful condition. So I'm looking forward to getting a chance to unwind with him today.

