[Amit Varma]: apps and at seen unseen.in. This is just a gesture of appreciation. Help keep this thing going.

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:23.980
[Amit Varma]: Seen unseen.in slash support.

00:05:27.340 --> 00:05:29.660
[Amit Varma]: Shruti and Alex, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:30.700
[Guest 1]: Great to be here.

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:31.820
[Amit Varma]: It's great to be here, Amit.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:37.180
[Amit Varma]: So Alex, you know, I've done a lot of episodes with Shruti where we've spoken about how she's

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:41.740
[Amit Varma]: gotten into economics, what influenced her, what books she liked and so on and so forth.

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:46.780
[Amit Varma]: We know everything about her. But, you know, when you and I did episodes back in the past,

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:50.700
[Amit Varma]: you know, we didn't discuss all that. I'm very curious to know what your journey has been like.

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:55.180
[Amit Varma]: How did you become an economist? Who were your big influences and so on?

00:05:55.180 --> 00:06:01.260
[Guest 2]: Oh, well, I think you'll like this because, as you probably know, the drummer from Rush,

00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:09.900
[Guest 2]: Neil Peart, died recently. And it was Rush which got me into libertarianism and economics,

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:16.140
[Guest 2]: you know, the incited Ayn Rand on one of their albums. And my mother had said,

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:21.100
[Guest 2]: this had come up and my mother had said, oh, you'd probably like her. And I think my mother

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:26.300
[Guest 2]: regrets saying that. Those are the worst things you possibly could say. Since then,

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:32.060
[Guest 2]: I started to read some Ayn Rand. So it was from Rush and from Neil Peart. So I've been

00:06:32.060 --> 00:06:35.980
[Amit Varma]: thinking a lot about that lately. And how did you kind of get into economics? Was it always

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:42.780
[Guest 2]: sort of an interest of yours or you stumbled into it? So I got into free market economics

00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:49.900
[Guest 2]: to begin with. And Ayn Rand recommended Ludwig von Mises as the greatest economist. So I read

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:57.100
[Guest 2]: some Mises. And then that brought me to Rothbard. I read a lot of Murray Rothbard's economics works,

00:06:57.100 --> 00:07:04.220
[Guest 2]: which were great. This was before university. I went to university with the idea of doing PPE,

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:11.420
[Guest 2]: politics, philosophy and economics. And in my first year, I did very, very well in economics

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:17.660
[Guest 2]: and not so good in politics and philosophy. So that kind of set my path.

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:20.540
[Amit Varma]: And tell me a little bit about, you know, Marginal Revolution, because,

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:24.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, I was an early blogger myself. And for anyone who's been into blogging,

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:28.540
[Amit Varma]: it is actually, you know, it is sort of the lodestar out there of what a great blog should be.

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:33.500
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how the age of blogs says, you know, essentially, it's over, blogs died,

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:37.660
[Amit Varma]: you know, social media took over all the utilities and the functions that a blog had. But Marginal

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:41.020
[Amit Varma]: Revolution is still, you know, culturally very significant as well.

00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:46.140
[Guest 2]: Yeah. So this was an interesting experiment. I actually said to Tyler, you know, we should

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:50.940
[Guest 2]: write a textbook. So this is more than 15 years ago now. And he said, yes, you're right. But first,

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:55.980
[Guest 2]: we should write a blog. And I think Tyler, as usual, had the ordering correct, because we began

00:07:55.980 --> 00:08:02.940
[Guest 2]: the blog. And as an interesting experiment, and within the first day or two of having posted

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:08.940
[Guest 2]: something, no, this is before Twitter is no, not even emailing people, people started to respond

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:14.060
[Guest 2]: to it. And I said, oh, maybe there's something to this. So we began writing the blog. And

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:19.580
[Guest 2]: the constraint of having to write concisely, having to get to the point, I think this really

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:24.540
[Guest 2]: makes you a much better writer, writing for a blog. You know, on the blog, when you write,

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:29.900
[Guest 2]: your audience is one click away from leaving you. So you have to give them something valuable.

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:33.420
[Guest 2]: And I think all of these techniques, which we learned in writing the blog,

00:08:33.420 --> 00:08:38.140
[Guest 2]: then poured it over into writing our textbook, Modern Principles of Economics.

00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:41.340
[Amit Varma]: And Shruti, one of the things I realized when I read your paper, and even the papers you've

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:46.620
[Amit Varma]: done earlier with Alex and others, is that this was a fun paper to read. You know,

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:51.180
[Amit Varma]: it was written in such a way that someone like me, who is not used to reading academic papers,

00:08:51.180 --> 00:08:54.300
[Amit Varma]: and Shruti is pointing at Alex here, it was written in such a way that someone like me,

00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:58.220
[Amit Varma]: who was not used to reading academic papers could, you know, just breeze through the whole

00:08:58.220 --> 00:09:01.900
[Amit Varma]: thing. Is that something that you've consciously put thought towards? I mean, I assume you would

00:09:01.900 --> 00:09:05.980
[Amit Varma]: say that doing Marginal Revolution and having to write Crispy and Concisely helped with that.

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:09.820
[Amit Varma]: What was your process of consciously thinking about how should we write papers? And B,

00:09:09.820 --> 00:09:15.820
[Amit Varma]: is it a feature or a bug given that, isn't it true that academics are almost expected to write

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:18.300
[Amit Varma]: in a certain kind of language as if for other academics?

00:09:18.940 --> 00:09:24.220
[Guest 2]: Yeah, there's a dangerous line that one doesn't want to cross. But especially when you're writing

00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:28.620
[Guest 2]: pieces which have some relevance to the real world, pieces which you want to influence people,

00:09:28.620 --> 00:09:34.540
[Guest 2]: have some policy, it really pays to write well. So Shruti and I did work on that aspect of the

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:39.820
[Guest 2]: paper quite a bit to make it readable for a general audience, as well as for, you know,

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:41.420
[Guest 2]: policymakers and academics.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:46.780
[Amit Varma]: And sort of a final question for you before we start talking about the paper itself, which is

00:09:46.780 --> 00:09:51.020
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, having lived in India all my life, there are a lot of things which for me are

00:09:51.020 --> 00:09:55.500
[Amit Varma]: normalized. Like I say that all of us tend to normalize the extreme coercion of the state,

00:09:55.500 --> 00:10:00.220
[Amit Varma]: and we don't think it unusual in any way. Now, with an outsider's perspective, when you look

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:05.740
[Amit Varma]: at India with the economic lens, with the policy lens, and so on, what are the things that strike

00:10:05.740 --> 00:10:10.620
[Amit Varma]: you as being very different from what you've otherwise seen? But you're amazed that, you know,

00:10:10.620 --> 00:10:12.940
[Amit Varma]: people here don't see it as something unusual.

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:18.780
[Guest 2]: I'm amazed that Indians do seem to put up with a lot from the state. You know, when I first came,

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:27.340
[Guest 2]: it was just after demonetization. And despite the huge costs which demonetization imposes,

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:32.460
[Guest 2]: as you well know, on shopkeepers and sellers in the street, and so forth, a lot of people

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:37.100
[Guest 2]: just accepted it. You know, they lined up for hours and hours, but did not protest in the

00:10:37.100 --> 00:10:42.220
[Guest 2]: streets. That was amazing to me, that there were not more people up in arms, that this stupid

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:50.380
[Guest 2]: policy, which was so costly to people, especially poorer people, that this did not create a uproar

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:55.740
[Guest 2]: and revolution even, you know, the way that you treat poor people, diminish the value of their

00:10:55.740 --> 00:11:02.140
[Guest 2]: time, you know, making them wait in line at the ATMs. And even today, it's amazing to me that

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:09.900
[Guest 2]: you still can't get change, right? So you have even a 500 rupee note, and still that's a problem,

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:17.500
[Guest 2]: not to speak of a 2000 rupee note. So even today, the state cannot find its way to supply

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:22.780
[Guest 2]: the right denominations in the right quantities to what people want. So that to me is amazing.

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:28.780
[Guest 2]: Very similar to this, I am amazed that people put up with so much pollution. You know, everyone

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:34.700
[Guest 2]: knows about it, but it just seems to be, well, there's nothing we can do. It's just like climate,

00:11:34.700 --> 00:11:39.180
[Guest 2]: you know, which is not climate. You know, this is manmade. This is not we're talking. I'm not

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:45.100
[Guest 2]: talking about, you know, increasing the temperature of the earth, you know, 1.5 degrees over the next

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:51.660
[Guest 2]: 100 years. I'm talking about today in Delhi, you know, the AQI, the pollution level is over 500,

00:11:51.660 --> 00:11:57.740
[Guest 2]: and it burns your eyes, and it gets into your throat, and it makes it harder to do a podcast,

00:11:57.740 --> 00:12:02.700
[Guest 2]: and all of these things. And yet people, they're not up in arms about it, as far as I can tell,

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:08.940
[Guest 2]: maybe they are behind the scenes. But Indians do seem to take a lot from the state and not expect

00:12:08.940 --> 00:12:13.100
[Amit Varma]: very much. Yeah, in fact, we're recording this in Delhi on Feb 10. And you've been here for a

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:18.460
[Amit Varma]: couple of weeks and have been complaining, among other things of the pollution, and I hear paper

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:22.860
[Amit Varma]: straws. Shruti, why does Alex not like paper straws? You don't like paper straws either?

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:29.580
[Guest 1]: Okay, so one is a question of preference, right? That paper straws get soggy, and so on, so forth.

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:34.380
[Guest 1]: Now, if you don't want to use single use plastic, and in the sense that we don't want to use a

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:39.580
[Guest 1]: plastic straw, then you could do with no straw at all. There are many substitutes for that.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:46.620
[Guest 1]: But the thing with paper straws is we see them at all the posh restaurants and cafes in Delhi.

00:12:46.620 --> 00:12:53.980
[Guest 1]: And to me, it seems like one of the best examples of elite imitation and virtue signaling,

00:12:53.980 --> 00:12:59.420
[Guest 1]: because the posh people in Delhi are up in arms about plastic straws, but not about air pollution,

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:07.100
[Guest 1]: right, which is literally killing their children, like infant morbidity and mortality is up in the

00:13:07.100 --> 00:13:12.860
[Guest 1]: winter in Delhi, simply because we have no handle on the pollution. But for the elites, the priority

00:13:12.860 --> 00:13:19.340
[Guest 1]: is not the pollution, or the priority is not one of these big ticket items. But it's something like,

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:23.340
[Guest 1]: let's get rid of single use plastic straws, because you know, that's going to do something

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:28.460
[Guest 1]: to seals in Alaska, or whatever the logic behind that is. It's even more puzzling that we do this

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:32.860
[Guest 1]: in India relative to the United States, because India has a huge plastic recycling industry.

00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:38.460
[Guest 1]: We recycle garbage for the rest of the world, right? There are shipments that come from

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:43.820
[Guest 1]: America and China, and it's processed here. So I would think we also have some kind of a

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:49.580
[Guest 1]: comparative advantage in recycling plastic single use or otherwise. So the whole thing is baffling

00:13:49.580 --> 00:13:55.260
[Guest 1]: to me, not because I don't like the idea of saving the planet one plastic straw at a time,

00:13:55.260 --> 00:14:02.140
[Guest 1]: that's a lovely thing to do. But because that is simply it cannot be even the top 500 priorities,

00:14:02.140 --> 00:14:07.500
[Guest 1]: let alone the top priority. And yet, that's the one thing that the elites have managed to lobby

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:14.860
[Guest 1]: change for. And every single cafe in India seems to have a paper straw instead of plastic straw,

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:20.220
[Guest 1]: like it's just the symptom of what is wrong with this kind of elite imitation and virtue signaling,

00:14:20.220 --> 00:14:22.540
[Guest 1]: where we're just not paying attention to the big problems.

00:14:22.540 --> 00:14:26.860
[Amit Varma]: And I guess one way of looking at this is that look, here's a problem that has an easy solution,

00:14:26.860 --> 00:14:31.500
[Amit Varma]: right? It's easy to find a solution which allows you to posture and, you know, appear concerned

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:35.500
[Amit Varma]: about the world and all of that. Now, if we might digress for a while and go to the pollution

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:39.420
[Amit Varma]: problem, because that's clearly something you guys have also thought about, I've done episodes on it

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:45.020
[Amit Varma]: where Delhi's air pollution, it seems to me is a ludicrously difficult problem to solve, and none

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:50.780
[Amit Varma]: of the intuitive solutions such as you know, Arvind Kejriwal's odd even work at any level.

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:55.260
[Amit Varma]: And the problem is like, you know, one of the things that exacerbates it in the winter months

00:14:55.260 --> 00:15:01.180
[Amit Varma]: is of course, farmers in Punjab burning rice stubble. And there's such a cascade of bad

00:15:01.180 --> 00:15:05.660
[Amit Varma]: incentives at play there. Because first of all, rice should not be grown in Punjab because

00:15:05.660 --> 00:15:10.540
[Amit Varma]: it's water intensive, Punjab is arid, but you have free electricity for farmers. So therefore,

00:15:10.540 --> 00:15:14.940
[Amit Varma]: they use tube wells, you have, you know, the government giving fixed prices for rice,

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:19.820
[Amit Varma]: and therefore incentivizing farmers in Punjab also to grow rice, all of those come together.

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:25.900
[Amit Varma]: And the way the politics plays out is no one's yet given me a satisfactory answer to how do we

00:15:25.900 --> 00:15:31.340
[Amit Varma]: sort this out? The people in Delhi may want cleaner air. But how do you put pressure on the

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:35.420
[Amit Varma]: politicians of Punjab who have to cater to the vote bank that they have?

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:40.780
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so I think part of the problem is to think that this is an issue of Punjab versus Delhi. And

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:45.020
[Guest 2]: the people in Punjab, of course, are rightly going to say, you know, why should we sacrifice,

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:51.420
[Guest 2]: you know, to make their air better. But in fact, the fumes and the smoke which is caused by the

00:15:51.420 --> 00:15:57.580
[Guest 2]: stubble burning in the Punjab is also killing the children of the Punjab. It's making the infants

00:15:57.580 --> 00:16:03.260
[Guest 2]: sick, it's making them stunted, it's making the elderly people have more cancer and heart disease

00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:08.860
[Guest 2]: and emphysema, it's making them harder to breathe as well. So the people in Punjab really need to

00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:12.700
[Guest 2]: understand, I think that the pollution is affecting them. It's not about saving other

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:18.700
[Guest 2]: people, it's about saving their own children and elderly. And I think moreover, as you point out,

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:25.900
[Guest 2]: the policy, there's a lot of low hanging fruit, in fact, because stubble burning is not a hugely

00:16:25.900 --> 00:16:33.420
[Guest 2]: profitable activity. It's not a big value creator for India, or even for the Punjab. So there's a

00:16:33.420 --> 00:16:40.140
[Guest 2]: lot of ways in which there are win-win solutions here, in which because the pollution is so bad,

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:44.700
[Guest 2]: because the costs are so high, and the benefits of something like stubble burning is so low,

00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:49.180
[Guest 2]: there are to be many, many ways in which everybody can come out better.

00:16:49.180 --> 00:16:54.140
[Guest 1]: There's an additional aspect to this. I've lived in Delhi most of my childhood years,

00:16:54.140 --> 00:16:58.940
[Guest 1]: they were always burning crop stubble in Punjab, right? But it was never so bad for Delhi because

00:16:58.940 --> 00:17:04.540
[Guest 1]: the base level air pollution in Delhi was never so bad that the additional pollution from the

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:10.620
[Guest 1]: stubble burning just pushed it beyond the limit. And here Delhi government and its policies are

00:17:10.620 --> 00:17:15.020
[Guest 1]: to blame too. Basically, the Supreme Court through a series of verdicts on the Delhi

00:17:15.020 --> 00:17:19.820
[Guest 1]: vehicular pollution, they try to get rid of the worst kind of pollution, which was diesel,

00:17:19.820 --> 00:17:25.980
[Guest 1]: right? So they banned bus fleet of about 10,000 buses. And they did it in such a weird way,

00:17:25.980 --> 00:17:30.300
[Guest 1]: because this was done through the Supreme Court, it was done by issuing writs. They basically told

00:17:30.300 --> 00:17:36.140
[Guest 1]: the Sheela Dixit government of the time that these buses can't run from tomorrow, right? So for a few

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:42.300
[Guest 1]: years, just like demonetization, we had this tremendous shock to the transportation system and

00:17:42.300 --> 00:17:47.020
[Guest 1]: a shortage, which meant that to go anywhere from point A to point B in Delhi, and this is all

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:53.900
[Guest 1]: before metro, and you know how large distances are in Delhi, people felt that the only way to

00:17:53.900 --> 00:17:59.900
[Guest 1]: actually travel is in a car. So even public transport in Delhi, if you notice is Inovas,

00:17:59.900 --> 00:18:04.140
[Guest 1]: right, they will pick up six or eight people and drive them to school, right? It used to be Maruti

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:12.060
[Guest 1]: Omnis, which is kind of like a minivan. So they completely decimated the public transport system.

00:18:12.060 --> 00:18:18.220
[Guest 1]: And we have 20 Inovas where you could have one bus. And we have 200 cars where you could have

00:18:18.220 --> 00:18:24.380
[Guest 1]: one bus, right? So Delhi needs to really think about its public transportation system. And the

00:18:24.380 --> 00:18:29.420
[Guest 1]: metro is not going to do it because the metro only takes you to certain like really important

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:35.100
[Guest 1]: major hubs. Everywhere else, Delhi is either too hot or too cold. It's not paved streets,

00:18:35.100 --> 00:18:39.980
[Guest 1]: it's hard to walk, they put road dividers everywhere, it makes it very pedestrian unfriendly.

00:18:39.980 --> 00:18:43.900
[Guest 1]: So the only way people can get from point A to point B effectively is in a car,

00:18:44.540 --> 00:18:49.500
[Guest 1]: right? So either they share the car services, or they have individual cars. But that's not a

00:18:49.500 --> 00:18:55.020
[Guest 1]: sensible way. And the other bizarre thing is in Delhi, you don't see any buses, or you don't see

00:18:55.020 --> 00:18:59.740
[Guest 1]: the number of buses per capita one would expect to see in a city like Delhi. You go to Bombay,

00:18:59.740 --> 00:19:04.140
[Guest 1]: everywhere you can see best buses. You just ask a random person who's been in Delhi for a few weeks,

00:19:04.140 --> 00:19:09.820
[Guest 1]: what is the public transportation flagship bus look or bus color? Alex, do you have any idea

00:19:09.820 --> 00:19:14.140
[Guest 1]: how a Delhi bus looks? No, I know. But you know how the Delhi Metro looks. And you know how the

00:19:14.140 --> 00:19:18.460
[Guest 1]: cars look. And you know, you've taken a tuk tuk, you've taken an e rickshaw. So it's one of those

00:19:18.460 --> 00:19:22.620
[Guest 1]: bizarre things that in Delhi, we just don't have enough buses. And this is all thanks to the

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:28.140
[Guest 1]: Supreme Court and the Delhi High Court, right? So we've managed to completely destroy any kind of

00:19:28.140 --> 00:19:35.100
[Guest 1]: public transportation policy. And we keep blaming Punjab. So what Alex said for Punjabi saving

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:40.300
[Guest 1]: themselves by not burning crop stubble, because very low value activity, I would say the same

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:47.900
[Guest 1]: thing to people living in Delhi about using cars, right? We need to lobby and we need to agitate for

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:54.220
[Guest 1]: better public transportation system. So today, as Alex pointed out on Feb 10, the air quality is

00:19:54.220 --> 00:19:59.660
[Guest 1]: 500 or higher. And as far as I know, no crop stubble is being burnt in Punjab and Haryana

00:19:59.660 --> 00:20:05.500
[Guest 1]: today or last week, and it won't be burnt next week. So we can't just blame Punjab and Haryana.

00:20:05.500 --> 00:20:09.900
[Guest 1]: Now, they're the worst 10 days of the year. But we have pretty bad air pollution in Delhi,

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:16.700
[Guest 1]: where Delhi needs its own set of policies, right to cope with vehicular pollution. Delhi is

00:20:16.700 --> 00:20:20.860
[Guest 1]: completely de-industrialized again, thanks to the Supreme Court. So we hardly have any industrial

00:20:20.860 --> 00:20:27.420
[Guest 1]: pollution. So this is just about road construction, metro construction, vehicular pollution that is

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:32.140
[Amit Varma]: causing these levels of pollution in Delhi. And these are all you know, transportation,

00:20:32.140 --> 00:20:36.780
[Amit Varma]: Delhi, these are all great separate episodes. And we shall now get back to the subject at hand,

00:20:36.780 --> 00:20:40.780
[Amit Varma]: which I was also reminded of when you mentioned metros, because you know, I was at this lit

00:20:40.780 --> 00:20:45.100
[Amit Varma]: fest yesterday in Nagpur, and they also have a metro there. And one of my friends made the

00:20:45.100 --> 00:20:48.860
[Amit Varma]: interesting point that, you know, it's almost become fashionable for Indian cities to install

00:20:48.860 --> 00:20:54.540
[Amit Varma]: metro. But the thing is that while it's great in Delhi and Bombay and cities that really need it,

00:20:54.540 --> 00:20:58.700
[Amit Varma]: in some cities, it is just not being used. Like in Nagpur, I think for a while, it was like eight

00:20:58.700 --> 00:21:03.660
[Amit Varma]: hours a day or something and people would just come in, you know, look around. So which gets us

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:09.420
[Amit Varma]: to the subject of your paper and the basic premise of your paper, if I can quickly state it briefly

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:17.020
[Amit Varma]: before we move on is that what we tend to do in India is that elite policymakers who are trained

00:21:17.020 --> 00:21:21.580
[Amit Varma]: abroad and you know, who are trained in the policies of other countries, or at least even if

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:26.940
[Amit Varma]: they are, you know, trained in India, they follow those intellectual fashions, tend to transplant

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:33.340
[Amit Varma]: policies that have worked in the West to India without considering local conditions or local

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:39.580
[Amit Varma]: state capacity. That's broadly it. And I'd sort of like to begin by asking you a bit about the

00:21:39.580 --> 00:21:44.220
[Amit Varma]: flailing state. What is a flailing state? And is India a flailing state?

00:21:44.860 --> 00:21:50.300
[Guest 2]: Yeah, a flailing state is one which cannot execute its own orders. It's one where the

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:58.140
[Guest 2]: head is not connected to the body. So in talking with people in India with the policymakers,

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:03.740
[Guest 2]: I'm always extremely impressed. The policymakers here are superb. They understand, they read all

00:22:03.740 --> 00:22:08.860
[Guest 2]: the journals, they're very familiar with everything, the latest techniques and so forth.

00:22:09.420 --> 00:22:15.740
[Guest 2]: But in India, the policymakers cannot control what happens in the driver's license bureau.

00:22:15.740 --> 00:22:22.940
[Guest 2]: So India, Delhi wants, I'm sure, to have people pass the driver's license. And yet we know that

00:22:22.940 --> 00:22:29.340
[Guest 2]: 30 percent of the people with a driver's license, it's fake. It's a fake license. Either they bribe

00:22:29.340 --> 00:22:34.860
[Guest 2]: somebody or something like that, or they're not even driving without a license. So India has,

00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:38.860
[Guest 2]: it knows where it wants to go. The head knows where it wants to do, but it can't get the body

00:22:38.860 --> 00:22:46.380
[Guest 2]: to do that. And the problem is, is that most of the experts in India and in the West,

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:51.980
[Guest 2]: they don't understand that and they don't make policy. In particular, they don't make policy

00:22:51.980 --> 00:22:59.820
[Guest 2]: with a recognition that what you want may not be what you get. If you want to make policy in India,

00:22:59.820 --> 00:23:05.020
[Guest 2]: you have to begin with the fact that you can only do a limited number of things.

00:23:05.020 --> 00:23:11.020
[Guest 2]: And what happens instead is that policymakers in India, they want to have everything that the West

00:23:11.020 --> 00:23:16.060
[Guest 2]: has. They want to have everything the United States has, including the regulation. So when

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:22.220
[Guest 2]: I look at regulation in India, there's no regulation in the United States that is not also

00:23:22.220 --> 00:23:28.540
[Guest 2]: here in India, right? And the plastic straw thing is an example of that. Whatever it is in the

00:23:28.540 --> 00:23:34.940
[Guest 2]: United States, whatever we're regulating in the U.S., you also regulate here in India. But India

00:23:34.940 --> 00:23:40.940
[Guest 2]: does not have the wealth nor the number of government employees. India has far fewer

00:23:40.940 --> 00:23:47.340
[Guest 2]: government employees than does the United States. In fact, India today is spending on government

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:52.700
[Guest 2]: about what the United States spent in, like, 1920. But they're trying to do much more than

00:23:52.700 --> 00:23:58.860
[Guest 2]: the United States did in 1920. So this is, I think, the main problem is that they're using

00:23:58.860 --> 00:24:05.500
[Guest 2]: 1920 resources to try and do 2020 regulation. And I think what we need, what India probably

00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:10.940
[Guest 2]: needs to do is to think, what can we do in 1920 resources? We should probably do 1920 regulation.

00:24:10.940 --> 00:24:16.860
[Guest 2]: And it would be a lot better if India stuck to what it can do, you know, the basics, you know,

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:22.620
[Guest 2]: clean water, clean air, law and order. These are things which the state can accomplish.

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:26.460
[Guest 2]: When it tries to do everything else, actually, these three things it can't do.

00:24:27.260 --> 00:24:32.300
[Guest 1]: My favorite quote on this is from Ed Glazer. I think we say this in the paper too.

00:24:32.300 --> 00:24:36.860
[Guest 1]: So a country that cannot provide clean water for its citizens should not be in the business

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:41.500
[Guest 1]: of regulating film dialogue, right? And that's my favorite quote. I mean, I think the government

00:24:41.500 --> 00:24:45.660
[Guest 1]: should not be in the business of regulating film dialogue anyway, lest the libertarians of the

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:50.780
[Guest 1]: world agitate against the three of us after hearing this. So I'm not in the business of that

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:54.940
[Amit Varma]: anyway. But even if you were to believe it should be regulated, it should be regulated,

00:24:54.940 --> 00:25:00.300
[Guest 1]: the Indian state should not be doing it because it simply can't, right? So you get a whole bunch

00:25:00.300 --> 00:25:06.860
[Guest 1]: of strange things going on because the state tries to do everything. In the process, it ends

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:11.820
[Guest 1]: up doing nothing, right? Or very little. So the government cannot enforce its own traffic

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:17.900
[Guest 1]: regulations. You will see all sorts of weird things. I've noticed this in Delhi. They start

00:25:17.900 --> 00:25:24.140
[Guest 1]: blocking off traffic signals because people don't obey the signals and they cannot afford a cop to

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:28.940
[Guest 1]: come and monitor the situation and hand out chalans to actually make people obey traffic

00:25:28.940 --> 00:25:34.060
[Guest 1]: rules. So in Delhi, people are in such a hurry that they just stop obeying traffic rules. So now

00:25:34.060 --> 00:25:39.740
[Guest 1]: what's the solution? The signal is blocked off. Important signals all over Delhi have been

00:25:39.740 --> 00:25:45.420
[Guest 1]: barricaded because we can't get people to use them the right way. So a city that can't get people

00:25:45.420 --> 00:25:50.700
[Guest 1]: to follow traffic rules, right, that can't enforce contracts, that cannot register the number of

00:25:50.700 --> 00:25:56.620
[Guest 1]: FIRs that come in every day, it simply should not try to do anything related to anything else.

00:25:56.620 --> 00:26:02.940
[Guest 1]: So while, forget the plastic straw thing with the paper straw, that just, it's a pet peeve. But

00:26:02.940 --> 00:26:08.540
[Guest 1]: even if, let's say, banning single-use plastic is a great idea, right? And I think the idea has

00:26:08.540 --> 00:26:13.340
[Guest 1]: some merit and we need to think about that a little bit more deeply. Even if it's a great idea,

00:26:13.340 --> 00:26:20.700
[Guest 1]: the Indian state cannot enforce it, right? And so our logic is, we shouldn't do it not because

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:27.100
[Guest 1]: it's a bad idea, it's because it can't be done. And you will slowly slip into a scenario where

00:26:27.100 --> 00:26:31.500
[Guest 1]: you don't enforce the plastic ban, then you don't enforce the next regulation, you don't enforce

00:26:31.500 --> 00:26:36.380
[Guest 1]: traffic regulation. And before you know it, it's a city full of criminals behaving lawlessly

00:26:36.380 --> 00:26:41.660
[Guest 2]: because you don't expect the state to enforce its own rules. Let me just underline one point there

00:26:41.660 --> 00:26:47.260
[Guest 2]: and maybe differ a little bit from Shruti. And that is this, I think the paper straw thing actually

00:26:47.260 --> 00:26:53.100
[Guest 2]: does tell us something because this is an example of virtue signaling. Now, this virtue signaling,

00:26:53.100 --> 00:26:59.020
[Guest 2]: the problem is in the US, well, it's just stupid, right? It's just virtue signaling,

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:05.500
[Guest 2]: but you can live with it, whatever. But here in India, virtue signaling detracts and takes away

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:12.700
[Guest 2]: resources from things which are really important. So the more resources you spend on banning plastic

00:27:12.700 --> 00:27:18.940
[Guest 2]: straws and plastic bags and things of that nature, the less resources you have to actually providing,

00:27:18.940 --> 00:27:24.380
[Guest 2]: you know, clean water and traffic signals. So here virtue signaling is a true vice,

00:27:24.380 --> 00:27:27.500
[Guest 2]: because it takes away from things which are really important.

00:27:27.500 --> 00:27:29.020
[Guest 1]: Yeah, it has a huge opportunity cost.

00:27:29.020 --> 00:27:30.460
[Guest 1]: Huge opportunity cost of virtue signaling.

00:27:30.460 --> 00:27:33.420
[Amit Varma]: Which is also in fact, just thinking a lot through of the public discourse,

00:27:33.420 --> 00:27:39.420
[Amit Varma]: like so much of the virtue signaling that happens on social media is fine in and of itself,

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:45.180
[Amit Varma]: but it takes away so much attentional capacity of people that people just then switch off social

00:27:45.180 --> 00:27:47.500
[Amit Varma]: media and we could be discussing more important things.

00:27:47.500 --> 00:27:53.340
[Guest 1]: Yeah, and our virtue signaling is a little bit bizarre. So as you know, the occupational hazard

00:27:53.340 --> 00:27:57.260
[Guest 1]: of being a professional academic is that you get invited a lot of conferences and

00:27:57.260 --> 00:28:02.860
[Guest 1]: panels and things like that. I feel like the Indian elite are much more concerned with the

00:28:02.860 --> 00:28:07.980
[Guest 1]: kind of diversity standards we have in America, as opposed to the kind of diversity standards we

00:28:07.980 --> 00:28:13.180
[Guest 1]: actually need in India, right? There is a lot of agitation against what they're calling manels.

00:28:13.180 --> 00:28:17.660
[Guest 1]: I am sure I've been invited to a whole bunch of panels just to make sure they're not manels,

00:28:17.660 --> 00:28:23.500
[Guest 1]: but I don't need help. I come from a lot of privilege. We have no similar agitation to get

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:29.180
[Guest 1]: Dalit voices on panels, for instance, right? Or diversity of thought, right? The rural urban

00:28:29.180 --> 00:28:33.500
[Guest 1]: divide. We won't pay money to get someone who lives in a village to actually come to Bombay or

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:39.740
[Guest 1]: Delhi and be on a panel and hear their voice. But we will make sure that we get LGBTQ representation

00:28:39.740 --> 00:28:44.860
[Guest 1]: and female representation. But in very large part, that's also it's not that that's not important.

00:28:44.860 --> 00:28:49.660
[Guest 1]: It's just it's elite imitation of what's happening in the West, because in the West,

00:28:49.660 --> 00:28:54.140
[Guest 1]: those are the really pressing problems in terms of within the academy. We don't have

00:28:54.140 --> 00:29:00.220
[Guest 1]: enough female voices and LGBTQ voices, right? In India, the problem's very different, right?

00:29:00.220 --> 00:29:04.380
[Guest 1]: Depending on which social strata you come from, you could be a very privileged

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:10.940
[Guest 1]: female or LGBTQ voice and are sort of oppressed groups are quite different.

00:29:11.740 --> 00:29:16.540
[Guest 1]: There's no such thing going on in America. America doesn't have Dalit affirmative action yet,

00:29:16.540 --> 00:29:22.460
[Guest 1]: right? So we're not copying that for India yet. So there is also a slightly more like myopic.

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:27.180
[Guest 1]: And if you know, this can take some sinister forms, but it's quite where we are looking and

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:31.340
[Guest 1]: who we are listening to is corrupted by this kind of elite imitation.

00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:36.460
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me that this kind of mimicry, elite imitation, whatever you call it,

00:29:36.460 --> 00:29:40.060
[Amit Varma]: is something that happens. I mean, we'll of course discuss the policy aspects of this,

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:45.020
[Amit Varma]: but it happens in all our thinking. For example, even ideologically, what we tend to have done,

00:29:45.020 --> 00:29:49.340
[Amit Varma]: and what you'll find common among political commentators who write in English and not so

00:29:49.340 --> 00:29:53.500
[Amit Varma]: much in the other languages is using that whole ideological frame of left and right

00:29:53.500 --> 00:29:57.740
[Amit Varma]: to talk about Indian politics. And it makes absolutely no sense here. I mean,

00:29:57.740 --> 00:30:01.980
[Amit Varma]: if you are to use that frame, then all parties are essentially statist and therefore left of

00:30:01.980 --> 00:30:06.460
[Amit Varma]: center when it comes to economics and kind of right to center because most of them

00:30:06.460 --> 00:30:11.820
[Amit Varma]: pander to majoritarian sentiments anyway. So the left right framework makes absolutely no sense.

00:30:11.820 --> 00:30:15.660
[Amit Varma]: And there have been attempts by some thinkers such as Rahul Verma, who I had on the show,

00:30:16.220 --> 00:30:20.620
[Amit Varma]: Pradeep Chhabber and Rahul Verma, they wrote an excellent book, excellent book about trying to

00:30:20.620 --> 00:30:24.940
[Amit Varma]: sort of, you know, find a new frame to look at what's actually happening here.

00:30:24.940 --> 00:30:29.020
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, so much of our ideological constructs and ways of thinking about the

00:30:29.020 --> 00:30:33.660
[Amit Varma]: world and especially when you talk about the posturing on Twitter, so much of the posturing

00:30:33.660 --> 00:30:40.060
[Amit Varma]: on Twitter is actually just replicating attitudes of the West, which may not really be sort of

00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:43.180
[Amit Varma]: relevant in an Indian context. I would completely agree.

00:30:43.180 --> 00:30:47.180
[Amit Varma]: Great. So let's get back to sort of the subject of the paper and what seems to sort of hit the

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:52.060
[Amit Varma]: nail on the head. And again, I'll quote from your paper here, quote, the Indian state flails because

00:30:52.060 --> 00:30:57.580
[Amit Varma]: it is simultaneously too large and too small, too large, because the Indian government attempts to

00:30:57.580 --> 00:31:02.860
[Amit Varma]: legislate and regulate every aspect of citizens lives, and too small, because it lacks the

00:31:02.860 --> 00:31:08.460
[Amit Varma]: resources and personnel to rule according to its ambitions. Stop quote. And you know,

00:31:08.460 --> 00:31:12.940
[Amit Varma]: as you were saying, Alex, just I'll quote some figures from your paper to demonstrate what

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:18.300
[Amit Varma]: those differences in state capacity are, where you say, quote, India has surprisingly few

00:31:18.300 --> 00:31:24.460
[Amit Varma]: government workers, about one fifth as many per capita as the United States, the number of police

00:31:24.460 --> 00:31:31.020
[Amit Varma]: per capita, for example, is only 135 per 100,000, one of the lowest rates in the world and far

00:31:31.020 --> 00:31:38.300
[Amit Varma]: below the median, which is 318, or mean 333 of police officers per 100,000 capita in the rest

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:43.340
[Amit Varma]: of the world. Moreover, a significant number of the police are assigned to VIPs rather than to

00:31:43.340 --> 00:31:48.780
[Amit Varma]: protecting the public at large. The number of judges per capita 12 per million is far below

00:31:48.780 --> 00:31:54.300
[Amit Varma]: the US rate 108 per million, which helps to explain India's enormous backlog of 32 million

00:31:54.300 --> 00:31:59.100
[Amit Varma]: cases, millions of which have been in process for more than a decade. Stop quote. I think I did an

00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:03.180
[Amit Varma]: episode with Alok Prasanna Kumar, where he mentioned some case that has been going on for

00:32:03.180 --> 00:32:09.420
[Guest 1]: 300 400 years. There are cases like that. So picking up on the judges thing, that's a good

00:32:09.420 --> 00:32:15.500
[Guest 1]: example. So judges have to enforce the rules, right, whatever the state has managed to legislate.

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:20.860
[Guest 1]: And if you think about it, the state is the biggest litigant before the courts, right anywhere,

00:32:20.860 --> 00:32:25.820
[Guest 1]: because both for disputes between different levels of government, and also all the criminal

00:32:25.820 --> 00:32:30.620
[Guest 1]: justice system, one of the parties is the state. So the state is one of the largest litigants,

00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:37.740
[Guest 1]: right. So in a sense, if we don't have enough judges, right, we're going to have long pendency

00:32:37.740 --> 00:32:43.020
[Guest 1]: of cases. But that gets exacerbated by the fact that you also have a lot of regulation. So let's

00:32:43.020 --> 00:32:47.900
[Guest 1]: say we have the capacity to deal with 100 cases a day, and there's some pendency related to that,

00:32:47.900 --> 00:32:53.180
[Guest 1]: you can make 80 of them on private contract enforcement, right, and 20 of them about some

00:32:53.180 --> 00:32:57.660
[Guest 1]: kind of regulation that wasn't followed. In India, the proportion is totally off,

00:32:57.660 --> 00:33:02.300
[Guest 1]: because the more things you regulate, the more it is going to clog up that capacity of 100 cases

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:08.380
[Guest 1]: that you can do in a day. So our pendency problems are only going to get worse, not better, even if

00:33:08.380 --> 00:33:14.540
[Guest 1]: we appointed more judges, unless we significantly roll back the regulatory state in India. And that

00:33:14.540 --> 00:33:20.380
[Guest 1]: just is not a priority for anyone, right. So when you look at civil servants, state capacity is now

00:33:20.380 --> 00:33:25.180
[Guest 1]: very fashionable. I've been talking to a lot of people, look at the major books on state capacity

00:33:25.180 --> 00:33:30.540
[Guest 1]: in India, all of them are talking about personnel problems, right? So that is one half of the

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:35.820
[Guest 1]: equation, we need more judges, we need more police, right? The other half of the equation is,

00:33:36.700 --> 00:33:42.140
[Guest 1]: in some sense, no matter how many judges and police we get, unless we roll back the regulation,

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:46.940
[Guest 1]: it's not going to do the job, right? If you continue regulating the way you have the last 70

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:53.020
[Guest 1]: years, all of India could be a cop and a judge, and it still won't do the trick. So we need to

00:33:53.020 --> 00:33:59.340
[Guest 1]: really think about the problem, like, as one of what is clogging the system, and what is addressing

00:33:59.340 --> 00:34:03.820
[Guest 1]: the clogs in the system. And the personnel and the money is just a small part of the problem.

00:34:03.820 --> 00:34:10.460
[Guest 2]: And these issues are really matter. So I have a paper with Vaidehi Tandel and Sahil Gandhi

00:34:10.460 --> 00:34:19.180
[Guest 2]: and Shamika Ravi, where we're looking at building construction in Mumbai. And what we find is that

00:34:19.180 --> 00:34:25.260
[Guest 2]: construction, on average, is delayed by 30%. The time to construct increases by about 30%,

00:34:25.260 --> 00:34:33.100
[Guest 2]: which is huge, because of litigation. And so litigation has become so easy with PILs and

00:34:33.100 --> 00:34:38.620
[Guest 2]: things like that, that you don't even have to win your case, right? If you want to hold up a

00:34:38.620 --> 00:34:43.820
[Guest 2]: construction project, you just sue, and then it goes to the court, and then it's just delayed.

00:34:43.820 --> 00:34:50.860
[Guest 2]: And so this gives, actually, a way of creating leverage. So the pendency itself is actually

00:34:50.860 --> 00:34:54.700
[Guest 2]: what is doing the work, because if the courts were quick, the suit wouldn't work.

00:34:54.700 --> 00:34:58.860
[Amit Varma]: The delay is a win. They wouldn't file a suit if they didn't know there would be a delay.

00:34:58.860 --> 00:35:03.740
[Guest 2]: Exactly. The delay is actually has become the threat point. So it's this combination, then,

00:35:03.740 --> 00:35:08.620
[Guest 2]: when you have all of this regulation, all of these reasons, which you might possibly sue,

00:35:08.620 --> 00:35:14.620
[Guest 2]: then you have delay, then that actually becomes powerful. And it becomes a way of extracting

00:35:14.620 --> 00:35:19.020
[Guest 2]: resources from people who are trying to build apartment buildings and things like that,

00:35:19.020 --> 00:35:24.300
[Guest 2]: which, obviously, Mumbai desperately needs. And both sides are exploiting the delay. Very often,

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:30.380
[Guest 1]: even the developers exploit the delay because they know that if there is a genuine case that

00:35:30.380 --> 00:35:36.460
[Guest 1]: the other party has, they won't have the power to litigate for 15 years, right? They won't be

00:35:36.460 --> 00:35:41.340
[Guest 1]: able to afford the legal fees. So let's say it's a dispute with a single homeowner who's the next

00:35:41.340 --> 00:35:46.380
[Guest 1]: door neighbor or something like that. That poor guy cannot afford legal fees for 15 years. They

00:35:46.380 --> 00:35:51.020
[Guest 1]: can't have their life put on hold for 15 years. But the developer probably has an entire legal

00:35:51.020 --> 00:35:54.860
[Amit Varma]: team. So it doesn't matter if you're right or wrong. The process is a punishment. Exactly.

00:35:54.860 --> 00:35:59.500
[Guest 1]: So depending on which side you're on, either side can exploit. I don't want to make it seem like,

00:35:59.500 --> 00:36:04.940
[Guest 1]: oh, only the poor developers get delayed. They also use the same system to exploit little guys

00:36:04.940 --> 00:36:09.500
[Guest 1]: when they try to take over land or illegally construct or all of those things. So this is a

00:36:09.500 --> 00:36:14.860
[Guest 1]: problem no matter which, no matter whose side you're on, in some sense, right? In the case of

00:36:14.860 --> 00:36:19.900
[Guest 1]: Bombay, the side we must all be on is how to quickly increase housing supply. So in this case,

00:36:19.900 --> 00:36:24.780
[Guest 1]: it really matters that the developers get delayed by 30% time because, I mean, that is going to

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:29.580
[Guest 1]: determine the delivery dates for the additional housing in Mumbai. It's also going to take up

00:36:29.580 --> 00:36:33.820
[Guest 1]: the cost of additional housing in Mumbai, right? So this is going to have all these cascading

00:36:33.820 --> 00:36:39.660
[Guest 1]: effects further downstream. We have to really think about capacity from that point of view.

00:36:39.660 --> 00:36:43.420
[Amit Varma]: And we'll talk about housing regulations a little bit later in the episode as one of the case

00:36:43.420 --> 00:36:47.100
[Amit Varma]: studies that you've sort of taken on. The phrase that struck me from your paper, which really

00:36:47.100 --> 00:36:51.900
[Amit Varma]: sums all of this up is regulatory overload, where, you know, the government keeps adding

00:36:51.900 --> 00:36:56.700
[Amit Varma]: regulations and state capacity and personnel and all of them sort of remain the same or grow really

00:36:56.700 --> 00:37:01.900
[Amit Varma]: slowly, if at all. And so my question there is that, is it therefore rational for a government

00:37:01.900 --> 00:37:07.020
[Amit Varma]: servant finding that he is overworked, there are too many regulations that he has to impose on too

00:37:07.020 --> 00:37:12.380
[Amit Varma]: many people? Is it rational for him to therefore become a rent seeker? Because rent seeking,

00:37:12.380 --> 00:37:17.260
[Amit Varma]: it strike me then is both more lucrative and easier than actual regulation.

00:37:17.980 --> 00:37:22.860
[Guest 1]: I have two ways to address this question. First is who is the government actor we're talking about,

00:37:22.860 --> 00:37:27.100
[Guest 1]: right? So if you think about the highest level bureaucracy, which is framing these rules,

00:37:27.100 --> 00:37:30.860
[Guest 1]: which is, you know, the Indian Civil Service, secretaries, joint secretaries,

00:37:30.860 --> 00:37:36.380
[Guest 1]: joint secretaries in the Ministry of Environment, and so on, so forth, they are not the guys who are

00:37:36.380 --> 00:37:42.060
[Guest 1]: on the ground taking the small bribes, right? So to some extent, it's not like their pockets

00:37:42.060 --> 00:37:46.300
[Guest 1]: directly get through. If there's any corruption happening at that level, it's a completely

00:37:46.300 --> 00:37:50.860
[Guest 1]: different game of, you know, thousands of crores going to Swiss bank accounts, coal licenses,

00:37:50.860 --> 00:37:55.500
[Guest 1]: exactly coal licenses. But our Indian Civil Service, you know, the one that's in Delhi,

00:37:55.500 --> 00:37:59.420
[Guest 1]: the people we've been talking to, they're actually remarkably corruption free,

00:37:59.420 --> 00:38:05.020
[Guest 1]: you know, relative to other state actors. And they are the people who are forming most of these rules,

00:38:05.020 --> 00:38:10.380
[Guest 1]: right? So to some extent, the guy who benefits from it, okay, downstream, the traffic cop who

00:38:10.380 --> 00:38:15.340
[Guest 1]: benefits from the stupid regulation, he's not the guy in charge of making the regulation. So I want

00:38:15.340 --> 00:38:20.700
[Guest 1]: to disconnect those two levels. My hunch is, if he asked a traffic cop, do you think we should

00:38:20.700 --> 00:38:25.980
[Guest 1]: have more regulation? He would say no, even though it benefits him in terms of higher, you know,

00:38:25.980 --> 00:38:30.620
[Guest 1]: some kind of rents or bribes or something like that. Because on a day to day basis,

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:36.060
[Guest 1]: they realize the kind of chaos it creates. They realize how little control they have over their

00:38:36.060 --> 00:38:41.580
[Guest 1]: own jobs. And they really don't make the rules that they are supposed to enforce. And no one

00:38:41.580 --> 00:38:47.180
[Guest 1]: has ever asked them on the input of their lived experience at their job on how we frame these

00:38:47.180 --> 00:38:52.460
[Guest 1]: rules. Similarly, a lot of the Delhi regulation that we just talked about in terms of transportation

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:58.220
[Guest 1]: or de-industrialization, it's all made by Supreme Court judges, right? They live in Lachchan's Delhi,

00:38:58.220 --> 00:39:04.300
[Guest 1]: they drive around India Gate Circle, which is now functioning really well, thanks to so many judges,

00:39:04.300 --> 00:39:08.700
[Guest 1]: you know, navigating that space, they go to Bhagwan Das Road, anything that's a problem

00:39:08.700 --> 00:39:14.860
[Guest 1]: between these two ends, they're aware of it. But they simply do not engage with regular folks,

00:39:14.860 --> 00:39:20.780
[Guest 1]: the guy at the licensing office, the guy who's a traffic cop, the guy who is going to enforce the

00:39:20.780 --> 00:39:25.740
[Guest 1]: Essential Commodities Act, who's the price controls inspector, labor inspector, no one

00:39:25.740 --> 00:39:30.700
[Guest 1]: seems to ask these people what to do, right? So I'd agree with you that rent seeking has led to

00:39:30.700 --> 00:39:36.460
[Guest 1]: this whole thing. If the price controls inspector was the guy writing the Essential Commodities Act,

00:39:36.460 --> 00:39:40.060
[Amit Varma]: but that's simply not the case. No, I'm arguing the other way. I'm not saying rent seeking has

00:39:40.060 --> 00:39:45.420
[Amit Varma]: led to this. I'm saying this has led to rent seeking as a natural and inevitable consequence

00:39:45.420 --> 00:39:50.380
[Amit Varma]: of very low state capacity having to deal with too many regulations. Like an example of this

00:39:50.380 --> 00:39:55.340
[Amit Varma]: came in Delhi, where there was news a few days ago that it takes something like 40 to 45 licenses,

00:39:55.340 --> 00:40:01.420
[Amit Varma]: documents, not licenses, 40 to 45 documents to open a business and 19 to get a gun, which means

00:40:01.420 --> 00:40:06.060
[Amit Varma]: if you want to start an assassination agency and have 20 documents, you will get a legal gun,

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:10.940
[Amit Varma]: but you'll be in the informal sector, kindly forgive bad joke. And another sort of instance

00:40:10.940 --> 00:40:15.180
[Amit Varma]: of over regulation is I had done an episode on restaurant regulations a while back with Madhu

00:40:15.180 --> 00:40:19.580
[Amit Varma]: Menon a couple of years back, where he pointed out that when he was running a restaurant,

00:40:19.580 --> 00:40:25.100
[Amit Varma]: the excise department had a regulation that he could only have one entrance to the restaurant,

00:40:25.100 --> 00:40:29.420
[Amit Varma]: so they could monitor the inflow and outflow of liquor. But the fire safety department quite

00:40:29.420 --> 00:40:34.060
[Amit Varma]: correctly mandated that there should be multiple entrances. So no matter what the guy does,

00:40:34.060 --> 00:40:38.940
[Amit Varma]: he is breaking the law, and there will be bribes and there will be rent seeking all across. But

00:40:38.940 --> 00:40:43.260
[Amit Varma]: like you pointed out, we have to disconnect the people who are benefiting from taking the bribes

00:40:43.260 --> 00:40:49.420
[Amit Varma]: inspectors on the ground from the policymakers. Why do the policymakers then like is it just

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:52.940
[Amit Varma]: the easiest thing to do put one more regulation to solve the problem?

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:57.180
[Guest 2]: I think that's what they're familiar with. Right. So again, they go to all of the international

00:40:57.180 --> 00:41:02.220
[Guest 2]: conferences, and they talk about best practices and the way to do things. And they come up with

00:41:02.220 --> 00:41:07.340
[Guest 2]: a list of things to do. And you know, we need public education, we need this, we need that we

00:41:07.340 --> 00:41:12.140
[Guest 2]: need this, and then they pass these laws. And then they can say to their friends, you know, in the

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:17.660
[Guest 2]: liberal sort of community, look at what we've done, you know, we pass this law, equal rights

00:41:17.660 --> 00:41:22.940
[Guest 2]: for women, the same wages for women, you know, all of this kinds of things. Even though this has no

00:41:22.940 --> 00:41:28.220
[Guest 2]: bearing whatsoever, on the actual situation in India, they can point to a law and say, see,

00:41:28.220 --> 00:41:33.260
[Guest 2]: we're just as advanced as you, we have the same law as you do. So I think that's part of it.

00:41:33.260 --> 00:41:37.340
[Guest 2]: I'm going back to what you said earlier, I'd also like to point out that perhaps the worst

00:41:37.340 --> 00:41:44.860
[Guest 2]: combination is to have honest bureaucrats and over regulation, right? These are the two things

00:41:44.860 --> 00:41:50.140
[Guest 2]: that go worse together, it may actually be the case. And sometimes it is the case that when you

00:41:50.140 --> 00:41:55.900
[Guest 2]: have all of this excess regulation, which cannot possibly be implemented, for some of the reasons

00:41:55.900 --> 00:42:00.620
[Guest 2]: that you said some of it is contradictory, and some of it, it just takes too many resources,

00:42:00.620 --> 00:42:06.780
[Guest 2]: it may actually the bribes, the petty bribes, which is the oil which makes the system flow.

00:42:06.780 --> 00:42:11.260
[Guest 2]: You know, unfortunately, what that means is that it is very difficult to get out of the system,

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:17.100
[Guest 2]: because people do benefit from the bribes. But the bribes, at least in some cases,

00:42:17.100 --> 00:42:21.980
[Guest 2]: have some positive aspects in that they let business actually get done. If every business

00:42:21.980 --> 00:42:26.700
[Guest 2]: had to go through those 42 regulations, India would have far fewer jobs and businesses than

00:42:26.700 --> 00:42:33.260
[Amit Varma]: they do today. So thank God for end seeking in a sense, because well, thank God for good

00:42:33.260 --> 00:42:37.980
[Guest 1]: corruption that greases the wheels and helps us overcome the problem of bad regulation.

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:41.740
[Amit Varma]: So it's a problem, in a sense, you would say created by the state and

00:42:41.740 --> 00:42:44.460
[Amit Varma]: solved by society through the mechanism of bribing.

00:42:44.460 --> 00:42:47.340
[Guest 1]: Yes. But that also makes criminals out of everybody.

00:42:47.340 --> 00:42:47.820
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:53.420
[Guest 1]: And it also gives state actors high moral ground when they want to put in more draconian regulation

00:42:53.420 --> 00:42:57.740
[Guest 1]: and stupid things like demonetization. Going back to the head of our conversation,

00:42:57.740 --> 00:43:03.740
[Guest 1]: demonetization, I have a feeling people tolerated it, because they were so tired of the corruption,

00:43:03.740 --> 00:43:09.020
[Guest 1]: right? And people hoarding black money, and rich people exploiting the system in a particular way.

00:43:09.020 --> 00:43:10.540
[Amit Varma]: So they bought the rhetoric that this will end.

00:43:10.540 --> 00:43:14.380
[Guest 1]: Exactly. So they bought the rhetoric that, you know, it's true that we are suffering,

00:43:14.380 --> 00:43:18.860
[Guest 1]: but the rich must be suffering so much more than us, right? And they really need to be punished

00:43:18.860 --> 00:43:22.700
[Guest 1]: for this kind of tax evasion and starving the state of funds and things like that.

00:43:22.700 --> 00:43:28.860
[Guest 1]: But that's also because the regular person doesn't understand political economy the same way

00:43:28.860 --> 00:43:33.580
[Guest 1]: we do once we read economics textbooks and we read case studies of how these things work out.

00:43:33.580 --> 00:43:37.180
[Guest 1]: And they're not expected to know these things, right? They're regular people,

00:43:37.180 --> 00:43:41.500
[Guest 1]: they're businessmen and farmers and, you know, housewives, they're just going about their daily

00:43:41.500 --> 00:43:46.620
[Guest 1]: life. So they can't even be expected to know this in some sense. But it's because we have made

00:43:46.620 --> 00:43:52.140
[Guest 1]: criminals of everyone that it gives people the high moral ground to make worse regulation,

00:43:52.140 --> 00:43:55.580
[Guest 1]: which just keeps adding to this problem in a bizarre way.

00:43:55.580 --> 00:44:00.860
[Guest 2]: And when everyone has been made a criminal, then when it comes to laws, which you actually do want,

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:06.940
[Guest 2]: you know, like traffic laws, like driver's licenses, like preventing pollution and low

00:44:06.940 --> 00:44:11.660
[Guest 2]: cost double burning and things like that, then the state can't do what is actually its job.

00:44:11.660 --> 00:44:18.780
[Guest 2]: So it's, again, this virtue signaling, this premature imitation, this overregulation,

00:44:18.780 --> 00:44:24.300
[Guest 2]: which makes it difficult to do the things which actually need to be done. So low state capacity

00:44:24.300 --> 00:44:32.300
[Guest 2]: means that the state can't even do the night watchman jobs, which even most libertarians

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:33.980
[Amit Varma]: would think that the state should do.

00:44:33.980 --> 00:44:38.220
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. I mean, what, you know, all of us keep arguing is that India needs a strong

00:44:38.220 --> 00:44:41.900
[Amit Varma]: state that does a few things well, rather than a weak state, which gets in the way.

00:44:41.900 --> 00:44:46.780
[Guest 1]: Yeah. And, you know, the only way that can happen is if each cop and, you know,

00:44:46.780 --> 00:44:51.580
[Guest 1]: sort of licensing inspector thought to themselves and said, Oh, I have 10 tasks,

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:55.420
[Guest 1]: I should prioritize the most important, which is the night watchman state.

00:44:55.420 --> 00:44:59.100
[Guest 1]: I think that is a very tall ask of any state actor.

00:44:59.100 --> 00:45:01.740
[Amit Varma]: You have to reduce his job to what is essential.

00:45:01.740 --> 00:45:06.060
[Guest 1]: Exactly. And actually, you got to get rid of most of those jobs. I don't know why we have

00:45:06.060 --> 00:45:09.820
[Guest 1]: an essential commodities act. I don't know why we have a labor inspection system.

00:45:09.820 --> 00:45:15.260
[Guest 1]: Right? These things simply shouldn't exist. And the second bizarre thing about the elite

00:45:15.260 --> 00:45:21.660
[Guest 1]: about the elite imitation part is not that Americans or people in Europe, those academics

00:45:21.660 --> 00:45:26.700
[Guest 1]: don't care about transportation, vehicular pollution. It's that they've solved the problem.

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:31.340
[Guest 1]: Right? So when you go to one of those conferences, they're only talking about

00:45:31.340 --> 00:45:35.340
[Guest 1]: single use plastic ban, because that's the problem they haven't solved yet.

00:45:35.340 --> 00:45:40.220
[Guest 1]: They've already solved the problem of congestion pricing. They already have an excellent bus fleet,

00:45:40.220 --> 00:45:45.500
[Guest 1]: they already have the highest level of regulation that you need on diesel vehicles or any kind of

00:45:45.500 --> 00:45:49.740
[Guest 1]: vehicle and the particulate matter that comes out of it. So they're not talking about those

00:45:49.740 --> 00:45:55.020
[Guest 1]: problems, not because they're not important. It's just they fix it. We are not talking about those

00:45:55.020 --> 00:46:00.460
[Guest 1]: problems, because they have fixed it. Right? That's the nature of the elite imitation,

00:46:00.460 --> 00:46:04.220
[Guest 1]: which is which makes the whole thing very strange. So we need to have a conversation

00:46:04.220 --> 00:46:08.780
[Guest 1]: just about transportation policy. Right? And then maybe 50 years later, we can talk about

00:46:08.780 --> 00:46:13.340
[Amit Varma]: single use plastic ban. Once we fix that problem. We'll talk more about our current

00:46:13.340 --> 00:46:40.780
[Amit Varma]: big problem of elite imitation. After we take a quick commercial break.

