[Amit Varma]: friend Shruti Rajgopalan and Alex Tabarrok about what is wrong with the elites. Now it's

00:47:47.100 --> 00:47:52.220
[Amit Varma]: commonly said by a lot of people with some justification that it is finally the elites

00:47:52.220 --> 00:47:57.260
[Amit Varma]: who drive policy and this is not necessarily a bad thing because the elites do have the training and

00:47:57.260 --> 00:48:01.420
[Amit Varma]: the understanding and the commitment to actually drive policy because you know, normal people

00:48:01.420 --> 00:48:06.380
[Amit Varma]: because of rational ignorance because they need to get on with their daily lives are not incentivized

00:48:06.380 --> 00:48:11.900
[Amit Varma]: to actually learn economics and understand how policy works. So eventually, all nations at the

00:48:11.900 --> 00:48:15.740
[Amit Varma]: level of policy and at the level of the founding principles are going to be driven by elites in a

00:48:15.740 --> 00:48:21.020
[Amit Varma]: sense, even our constitution was made by elites. And I shall come back to that question later of

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:26.060
[Amit Varma]: whether that was an example of elite imitation. But in your paper, you've you point out that

00:48:26.060 --> 00:48:30.460
[Amit Varma]: there is a grave danger to this as well. Can you elaborate on that a little bit?

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:37.020
[Guest 2]: Yeah, let me give an example. I was in Bangalore and I needed some medicine. And so there was a

00:48:37.020 --> 00:48:42.780
[Guest 2]: sort of a hospital nearby with a pharmacy and I went to the pharmacy. And I was quite amazed

00:48:42.780 --> 00:48:48.220
[Guest 2]: because I mean, it looked just like Kaiser just it looked just like at home. Okay, I was very

00:48:48.220 --> 00:48:53.740
[Guest 2]: comfortable because I walked in. And yet, and I was comfortable because all of the signs were in

00:48:53.740 --> 00:49:00.700
[Guest 2]: English. And I got the medicine and the explanation for how to use the medicine is all in English.

00:49:00.700 --> 00:49:06.300
[Guest 2]: And this is not because of me personally, you know, the white guy. This is just the way the

00:49:06.300 --> 00:49:12.540
[Guest 2]: hospital works. And I can guarantee you, I mean, I'm sure this was an elite hospital in some sense,

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:17.740
[Guest 2]: but I can guarantee you just by listening to the people there that not all of the patients spoke

00:49:17.740 --> 00:49:23.500
[Guest 2]: English. So this was something which was amazing to me in that the elites, you know, and I don't

00:49:23.500 --> 00:49:29.580
[Guest 2]: want to criticize the doctors. I'm sure the doctors spend time communicating in their native

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:36.540
[Guest 2]: tongue to some of the patients as best as they can. But the system itself was totally geared

00:49:36.540 --> 00:49:43.900
[Guest 2]: to English speaking, not to speaking in native tongue. And that to me was an example of premature

00:49:43.900 --> 00:49:49.020
[Guest 2]: and elite imitation, which I think has very negative consequences.

00:49:49.020 --> 00:49:55.900
[Guest 1]: Yeah, and English is the 44th most fluent language spoken in India. So there are 43 languages,

00:49:56.460 --> 00:49:58.540
[Guest 1]: which have higher fluency levels.

00:49:59.660 --> 00:50:00.220
[Amit Varma]: Measured how?

00:50:00.940 --> 00:50:06.780
[Guest 1]: I think this is the IHDS survey. I think we cite this in the paper, I can look it up and tell you.

00:50:06.780 --> 00:50:10.780
[Guest 1]: But this is basically how many people speak a language in India, like the,

00:50:11.660 --> 00:50:17.820
[Guest 1]: in terms of population, and then how fluent they say they are in the survey questions, right? So

00:50:17.820 --> 00:50:25.100
[Guest 1]: I'm a native level English speaker, right? I'm a native level Hindi speaker. But my reading skills

00:50:25.100 --> 00:50:29.100
[Guest 1]: in Hindi are a little bit rusty, because it's been a while since I've been exposed to reading

00:50:29.100 --> 00:50:34.700
[Guest 1]: books in Hindi, right, simply by virtue of living in the United States for so long. Now, if you can

00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:39.340
[Guest 1]: speak English, but your fluency levels are really in Hindi, and now I'm talking only about the

00:50:39.340 --> 00:50:43.980
[Guest 1]: literate population of India, which is also not the entire population. You can't understand

00:50:43.980 --> 00:50:45.180
[Guest 1]: medical terminology.

00:50:45.180 --> 00:50:48.860
[Guest 1]: It's actually an effort to read a sign in English. You have to decipher it.

00:50:48.860 --> 00:50:52.220
[Guest 1]: And you know, signs are easy, because you get used to them, you go to the same places over

00:50:52.220 --> 00:50:56.940
[Guest 1]: and over again. Medicines, as Alex points out, is a really big problem. You're usually taking

00:50:56.940 --> 00:51:00.700
[Guest 1]: medicines when you're not feeling too well, someone else might be administering them to you,

00:51:01.260 --> 00:51:07.100
[Guest 1]: right? At that point in time, if you don't understand what the directions are to take

00:51:07.100 --> 00:51:11.900
[Guest 1]: the medicine, unless they're explained to you, or they're texted to you in another language,

00:51:11.900 --> 00:51:15.900
[Guest 1]: it's a really big problem. So in a sense, the Indian elites have colonized their own people,

00:51:16.860 --> 00:51:21.580
[Guest 1]: using a language that the elites are comfortable with, that most of India is simply not comfortable

00:51:21.580 --> 00:51:22.060
[Guest 2]: with.

00:51:22.060 --> 00:51:23.900
[Guest 1]: You were saying about your grandmother?

00:51:23.900 --> 00:51:29.260
[Guest 1]: Yeah, my grandmother, I mean, she knew a few words in English, right? But she was not

00:51:29.260 --> 00:51:33.660
[Guest 1]: anywhere close to a, even a fluent English speaker, forget native English speaker,

00:51:34.380 --> 00:51:38.700
[Guest 1]: she couldn't go to the doctor alone. And this is not unique to my grandmother, right?

00:51:38.700 --> 00:51:43.740
[Guest 1]: Someone has to take most grandmothers to the doctor, not because they're loving and polite,

00:51:43.740 --> 00:51:48.220
[Guest 1]: but because there's a very high chance that they won't understand the instructions,

00:51:48.220 --> 00:51:53.580
[Guest 1]: unless the doctor makes an effort to explain it to them in their native tongue, right?

00:51:53.580 --> 00:51:57.980
[Guest 1]: Which is not always the case, right? Now, imagine this at higher and higher levels. Now,

00:51:57.980 --> 00:52:02.700
[Guest 1]: this may be just a question of, you know, some written material on an antibiotics box

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:05.500
[Guest 1]: or something like that. And you can get a neighbor to help you with it.

00:52:05.500 --> 00:52:10.700
[Guest 1]: What about information like surgery, right? You go to a hospital, doctors give you a whole

00:52:10.700 --> 00:52:15.900
[Guest 1]: lot of information, right? The doctors are not using their native tongue, because they're part

00:52:15.900 --> 00:52:21.580
[Guest 1]: of the elite. And the people who are receiving that information may simply not be able to process

00:52:21.580 --> 00:52:25.580
[Guest 1]: it, not because they're stupid, not because they're not smart, or they can't run their own

00:52:25.580 --> 00:52:31.900
[Guest 1]: lives. But because we have imposed this bizarre language on them. It's the same thing with forms,

00:52:31.900 --> 00:52:37.820
[Guest 1]: right? You go anywhere in India, and you fill any form, it's English, and now increasingly Hindi,

00:52:37.820 --> 00:52:42.780
[Guest 1]: there's a big push for Hindi. But we don't see too many forms in native languages. And if it's

00:52:42.780 --> 00:52:46.860
[Guest 1]: in a native language, it's usually only the one language, right, the dominant language of the

00:52:46.860 --> 00:52:53.260
[Guest 1]: state. But in India, as we know, even the minority language in any state is like 12 million people

00:52:53.260 --> 00:52:59.260
[Guest 1]: speak that language, right? So we effectively exclude 12 million people from being able to

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:05.020
[Guest 1]: successfully fill a form out easily. So this just happens over and over again, wherever you go.

00:53:05.020 --> 00:53:11.180
[Guest 1]: The legal system is entirely in English, right? The higher level courts are in English. So this

00:53:11.180 --> 00:53:17.260
[Guest 1]: has some really big problems in terms of access, right? Access to pretty much anything. That's why

00:53:17.260 --> 00:53:22.060
[Guest 1]: learning English has such a big premium in India. We always thought it's about jobs, right? And I'm

00:53:22.060 --> 00:53:28.620
[Guest 1]: sure that's a very large part of it. But it's also about just navigating sophisticated systems,

00:53:28.620 --> 00:53:32.700
[Guest 1]: which you need in terms of medical care, you need in terms of being able to fill out a form

00:53:32.700 --> 00:53:38.140
[Guest 1]: effectively for all the paperwork. We are not able to do it in India without additional human

00:53:38.140 --> 00:53:44.060
[Guest 2]: interface. I want to make the point, I mean, it's great that lots of Indians speak English. I mean,

00:53:44.060 --> 00:53:49.820
[Guest 2]: it is a strength of the country that so many people are willing to learn multiple languages.

00:53:49.820 --> 00:53:55.740
[Guest 2]: I mean, this is a positive thing. And it's a powerful thing that enables Indians to reach out

00:53:55.740 --> 00:54:00.780
[Guest 2]: and get the best scientific literature and so forth. But, you know, it's often been said that

00:54:00.780 --> 00:54:07.020
[Guest 2]: India is more like, you should think about India like Europe, right, as a collection of countries.

00:54:07.020 --> 00:54:12.780
[Guest 2]: And yet in Europe, you know, there would be no situation in which in Germany, you know,

00:54:12.780 --> 00:54:17.740
[Guest 2]: you would find all of the instructions in French, right? Or, you know, in Italy,

00:54:18.300 --> 00:54:23.100
[Guest 2]: you would find everything, you know, written in German. This just does not happen, right?

00:54:23.100 --> 00:54:30.300
[Guest 2]: And so this is another example of a situation where the elites operate in a different world

00:54:30.300 --> 00:54:36.860
[Guest 2]: and make assumptions which are imposed over all of India. So if India truly is like Europe,

00:54:36.860 --> 00:54:43.900
[Guest 2]: and it is, then the state ought to be paying much more attention to speaking to the populace

00:54:43.900 --> 00:54:48.780
[Amit Varma]: in the language which they understand. This is, it seems to me to be kind of a muddy problem in

00:54:48.780 --> 00:54:53.660
[Amit Varma]: the sense that yeah, obviously, I completely agree with you. And by your point that, you know, much

00:54:53.660 --> 00:54:57.580
[Amit Varma]: as in Indian homes, you will find the kitchen is often the grottiest room because the men are

00:54:57.580 --> 00:55:01.340
[Amit Varma]: making the decisions and they don't spend too much time in the kitchen. So similarly, elites

00:55:01.340 --> 00:55:05.660
[Amit Varma]: are comfortable in English. So they are imposing English on the country. I get that. But at the

00:55:05.660 --> 00:55:11.420
[Amit Varma]: same time, there is also that imperative after independence that we are a country with so many

00:55:11.420 --> 00:55:16.060
[Amit Varma]: linguistic divides. And you know, you would have started a civil war if you tried to impose Hindi

00:55:16.060 --> 00:55:21.340
[Amit Varma]: on Tamil Nadu. And English was a functional language everywhere. So why not go with it?

00:55:21.340 --> 00:55:25.740
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that is different from the analogy of Europe, because in Europe,

00:55:25.740 --> 00:55:30.780
[Amit Varma]: they're all independent nation states. While here you've got to and obviously, our elites also did

00:55:30.780 --> 00:55:36.140
[Amit Varma]: have a vision where you know, they pay tribute to federalism only in name, it was they were basically

00:55:36.140 --> 00:55:41.420
[Amit Varma]: governing from the center. And therefore, as a functional language, it would seem to me that

00:55:41.420 --> 00:55:46.540
[Amit Varma]: English was, you know, just the obvious rational choice, which then leads to what is both a vicious

00:55:46.540 --> 00:55:50.780
[Amit Varma]: circle and a virtuous circle. It's a virtuous circle in the sense that if you learn English,

00:55:50.780 --> 00:55:55.340
[Amit Varma]: you get ahead in life, and so on and so forth. It's a vicious circle for those left out of it,

00:55:55.340 --> 00:56:00.380
[Amit Varma]: that you're deepening social and economic inequalities to those who do not have access

00:56:00.380 --> 00:56:05.740
[Amit Varma]: to English and to English education. And I don't know what's the way out of this, because it seems

00:56:05.740 --> 00:56:10.780
[Amit Varma]: to me that if you regulate it, you know, if you regulate local governance in multiple languages,

00:56:10.780 --> 00:56:14.300
[Amit Varma]: you run into the same problems of state capacity, which we've been speaking about.

00:56:14.300 --> 00:56:18.860
[Guest 1]: So I would say two things. One, I love the linguistic diversity of India, I wouldn't

00:56:18.860 --> 00:56:24.220
[Guest 1]: change it. I also like that the official language is English if for no other reason than self serving,

00:56:24.220 --> 00:56:27.980
[Guest 1]: because it helps me navigate everything. So I understand the problems that you know,

00:56:27.980 --> 00:56:31.900
[Guest 1]: India had this high degree of linguistic fractionalization. So you needed some

00:56:32.540 --> 00:56:37.020
[Guest 1]: common language that no one would dispute and English ended up being that language. So that's

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:43.580
[Guest 1]: fine. My issue is more in terms of lack of user sensitivity, right? We're not thinking about

00:56:44.140 --> 00:56:49.980
[Guest 1]: who is actually using these documents. If we mandate ISI standards, and a written set of

00:56:49.980 --> 00:56:56.220
[Guest 1]: instructions for how to use an iron, we are not thinking about can the person buying the iron

00:56:56.220 --> 00:57:02.620
[Guest 1]: actually read the instructions, right? Anytime we buy any of these Chinese electronic gadgets that

00:57:02.620 --> 00:57:07.660
[Guest 1]: I use in America, it's like a really long piece of paper that's folded in, it's got a tiny set

00:57:07.660 --> 00:57:11.580
[Guest 1]: of instructions, but it's in at least 16 different languages, because the Chinese are making and

00:57:11.580 --> 00:57:16.060
[Guest 1]: exporting to the world. They're cognizant of that, because they think like an entrepreneur.

00:57:16.940 --> 00:57:19.260
[Guest 1]: And they care that the user can actually read the instructions.

00:57:19.260 --> 00:57:20.380
[Amit Varma]: And they're responding to incentives.

00:57:20.380 --> 00:57:24.940
[Guest 1]: And they're responding to incentives, which you know, so what I mean by we've colonized our own

00:57:24.940 --> 00:57:30.380
[Guest 1]: people in a foreign language is not that I think English is bad medium. It's simply that we haven't

00:57:30.380 --> 00:57:37.020
[Guest 1]: made any effort to understand, if it helps the people it's supposed to help, right? We have all

00:57:37.020 --> 00:57:41.900
[Guest 1]: this staggering amount of information that we want to give on medical boxes and medical forms.

00:57:41.900 --> 00:57:45.340
[Guest 1]: And we don't think for a second about who's actually going to read those medical forms,

00:57:45.340 --> 00:57:50.380
[Guest 1]: right? We don't think about do we have translation services. Now, every pharmacist,

00:57:50.380 --> 00:57:56.140
[Guest 1]: every hospital compounder doctor we know acts as a mini translation service. So you and I who've

00:57:56.140 --> 00:58:00.620
[Guest 1]: navigated the system, we know that the kind doctors immediately switch to another language

00:58:00.620 --> 00:58:06.460
[Guest 1]: and things like that. But what I mean is the state has not put in any effort on how we design a

00:58:06.460 --> 00:58:13.420
[Guest 1]: system. Keeping in mind citizens, we design systems keeping in mind bureaucrats, right?

00:58:13.420 --> 00:58:18.060
[Guest 1]: So that's kind of my problem with English as the official language. It is not that costly,

00:58:18.060 --> 00:58:25.020
[Guest 1]: especially given current technology levels to have all court cases and judgments translations

00:58:25.020 --> 00:58:29.820
[Guest 1]: made available in multiple languages. We simply don't do it. I don't know why, right? So only if

00:58:29.820 --> 00:58:35.340
[Guest 1]: you know English, you can get access to all the Supreme Court important judgments, some of the

00:58:35.340 --> 00:58:40.540
[Guest 1]: most important things that govern state and citizen relations. The same thing for the budget,

00:58:40.540 --> 00:58:44.460
[Guest 1]: right? Only in the last two or three years have we had the budget speech in Hindi. We don't

00:58:44.460 --> 00:58:51.260
[Guest 1]: translate to other languages. What we do is the local regional language news channel will do a

00:58:51.260 --> 00:58:55.740
[Guest 1]: translation of some sort of what the finance minister said in Parliament. And that's how

00:58:55.740 --> 00:59:01.100
[Guest 1]: they inform that, you know, speakers of that language. But we don't have language translation

00:59:01.100 --> 00:59:06.700
[Guest 1]: easily available. I'm just saying government should make documents at the very least available

00:59:06.700 --> 00:59:10.700
[Guest 1]: in languages that people speak. And I'm not talking about languages that you know,

00:59:10.700 --> 00:59:15.420
[Guest 1]: small minority speaks, I'm talking about languages that 30, 40, 50 million people speak,

00:59:15.420 --> 00:59:22.460
[Guest 1]: so it will eventually pay for itself. But it also is a symptom of how the state thinks about

00:59:22.460 --> 00:59:28.940
[Guest 1]: its people as subjects, and not as citizens or like users of public services. And that,

00:59:28.940 --> 00:59:32.700
[Guest 1]: to me is the most disturbing thing about this entire language issue.

00:59:32.700 --> 00:59:37.740
[Amit Varma]: Very well said. You say in your paper, quote, we identify three characteristics of the Indian

00:59:37.740 --> 00:59:42.940
[Amit Varma]: elite, especially of those formulating policy, language, caste and education at institutions

00:59:42.940 --> 00:59:47.180
[Amit Varma]: outside of India, stop quote. And the reason you point this out is obviously because all of these

00:59:47.180 --> 00:59:52.220
[Amit Varma]: are factors in the kind of elite imitation that eventually gets us into a spot. So can you

00:59:52.220 --> 00:59:58.140
[Guest 2]: elaborate a bit on this? Let me take the least controversial one, and I'll let Trudy do the

00:59:58.140 --> 01:00:05.180
[Guest 2]: more controversial ones, but the education of the elites outside of India. Now, in part, this is a,

01:00:05.180 --> 01:00:12.140
[Guest 2]: to me as an outsider is a remarkably positive element in that it's amazing that someone like

01:00:12.140 --> 01:00:20.620
[Guest 2]: Raghuram Rajan could come into India, become the head of the RBI, and then leave and go back,

01:00:21.500 --> 01:00:25.020
[Guest 2]: you know, to teach at Chicago or Harvard or wherever he is now.

01:00:25.020 --> 01:00:29.020
[Amit Varma]: And get to so many people, Arvind Panagari, Arvind Subramanian, blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:00:29.020 --> 01:00:35.500
[Guest 2]: Arvind Subramanian Exactly. There's many, many examples of this. So in one sense, it's remarkably positive

01:00:35.500 --> 01:00:42.380
[Guest 2]: that it shows something about the confidence of India that they could accept as someone,

01:00:42.380 --> 01:00:48.140
[Guest 2]: as Indian could come in for a few years and advise the government. That is something which

01:00:48.140 --> 01:00:52.540
[Guest 2]: you would never see, I think, in the United States, right? Somebody who lives somewhere else

01:00:52.540 --> 01:00:59.980
[Guest 2]: to come into the United States, it just wouldn't happen. And I do applaud Indians for that,

01:00:59.980 --> 01:01:09.020
[Guest 2]: because I think it's positive. On the other hand, it's clearly also the case that this biases policy

01:01:10.140 --> 01:01:17.500
[Guest 2]: in ways where the head policymakers are thinking about an audience back home. They know they're

01:01:17.500 --> 01:01:23.100
[Guest 2]: not going to be here that long. They know this is not a permanent position. They do not live in the

01:01:23.100 --> 01:01:28.780
[Guest 2]: country. They don't even live in, you know, a colony in Delhi like some of the Supreme Court

01:01:28.780 --> 01:01:35.180
[Guest 2]: judges Shruti was mentioning. They at least live and see the country where some of the

01:01:35.740 --> 01:01:41.340
[Guest 2]: policymakers who helicopter in for a few years, they're not even that close. So I do think that

01:01:41.340 --> 01:01:49.660
[Guest 2]: it biases policy. And that's that's important. And it's reflected throughout a lot of the

01:01:49.660 --> 01:01:57.420
[Guest 1]: Indian elite. I would add a few things to this. So one is, again, every system is going to produce

01:01:57.420 --> 01:02:03.980
[Guest 1]: a particular type of elite, right? And every system has structural reasons why very similar

01:02:03.980 --> 01:02:10.220
[Guest 1]: looking people end up in the elite. So in America, we have this huge debate going on about how white

01:02:10.220 --> 01:02:15.660
[Guest 1]: men have a particular kind of privilege. If you have multi generations of, you know, college

01:02:15.660 --> 01:02:20.940
[Guest 1]: education in your family, you have a particular kind of privilege, a huge row all over the US

01:02:20.940 --> 01:02:26.460
[Guest 1]: with Ivy League schools is how if your parents have been to that school, you get some preferential

01:02:26.460 --> 01:02:31.180
[Guest 1]: treatment to go to those Ivy League schools, and so on, so forth. So every country, every society

01:02:31.180 --> 01:02:38.540
[Guest 1]: is going to have some structure of privilege. The kind of privilege that has taken place in India,

01:02:38.540 --> 01:02:45.100
[Guest 1]: right, is that typically, upper caste people manage to capture really important areas,

01:02:45.660 --> 01:02:50.300
[Guest 1]: virtually in any sector of society, right? So whether you talk about business,

01:02:50.300 --> 01:02:54.220
[Guest 1]: whether you talk about academics, whether you talk about teaching at the school,

01:02:54.220 --> 01:03:00.540
[Guest 1]: whatever it is, it is, I mean, blindingly obvious, no one has to make big arguments

01:03:00.540 --> 01:03:05.900
[Amit Varma]: to make the case that it is, you know, and let someone misunderstand what you obviously mean is

01:03:05.900 --> 01:03:11.660
[Amit Varma]: that it is a structure which has these inequities built in. It is not necessary that there is some

01:03:11.660 --> 01:03:17.180
[Amit Varma]: person at the top who is discriminating and out of you know, all the candidates choosing only the

01:03:17.180 --> 01:03:21.340
[Amit Varma]: upper caste guys. The problem is that out of all the candidates he will get there will mainly be

01:03:21.340 --> 01:03:25.180
[Guest 1]: upper caste. Yes, and all the people doing the choosing will be upper caste, all the people

01:03:25.180 --> 01:03:29.260
[Guest 1]: applying will be upper caste, what you get is a panel full of upper caste. And this perpetuates

01:03:29.260 --> 01:03:34.540
[Guest 1]: itself. So it has perpetuated itself. It's appalling in India that we have, we pay very

01:03:34.540 --> 01:03:40.700
[Guest 1]: little attention to diversity in every area of life other than reservation of government jobs.

01:03:40.700 --> 01:03:45.500
[Guest 1]: That's the only area where you know, there is a constitutional mandate, we've paid some attention

01:03:45.500 --> 01:03:51.420
[Guest 1]: to it. Every other area, the moment you talk about any kind of structural inequality, the moment you

01:03:51.420 --> 01:03:57.420
[Guest 1]: talk about taking representation seriously, you encourage private companies to have, you know,

01:03:57.420 --> 01:04:01.340
[Guest 1]: affirmative action to have greater representation, they'll say no, those people can go get government

01:04:01.340 --> 01:04:06.460
[Guest 1]: jobs, right. So it's become a very strange system where we don't have representation across the

01:04:06.460 --> 01:04:12.780
[Guest 1]: board. Now. So in India, we know what the elite looks like. The elite typically is upper caste

01:04:12.780 --> 01:04:18.220
[Guest 1]: more often than not Brahmin, but certainly upper caste. The elite also speak English,

01:04:18.220 --> 01:04:24.780
[Guest 1]: right? Probably multi generationally, they speak English, not just their own generation. And third,

01:04:25.660 --> 01:04:30.700
[Guest 1]: they have access to highest quality education, right? Sometimes it's the highest quality

01:04:30.700 --> 01:04:36.860
[Guest 1]: education in India, like IITs, and or IIMs, you know, all the elite schools. And very often,

01:04:36.860 --> 01:04:41.420
[Guest 1]: if they come from a particular kind of privilege, they're able to go abroad and get, you know, a

01:04:41.420 --> 01:04:46.460
[Guest 1]: PhD or a business degree or whatever it is abroad. Now, this has been going on for more than 100

01:04:46.460 --> 01:04:52.540
[Guest 1]: years, right? The last set of local elites we produced who were just purely local were people

01:04:52.540 --> 01:04:59.180
[Guest 1]: like Dadabhai Naoroji, who were completely educated in India. So everyone, starting with Nehru, a lot

01:04:59.180 --> 01:05:04.380
[Guest 1]: of the people who wrote the constitution, they were all elite. Now, speaking of the elite problem,

01:05:04.380 --> 01:05:09.180
[Guest 1]: why is this an issue? So Ambedkar famously said that only people who haven't lived in villages,

01:05:09.180 --> 01:05:14.620
[Guest 1]: romanticize villages, because the people who romanticize villages and don't want urbanization

01:05:14.620 --> 01:05:20.700
[Guest 1]: and want rural development, are all these upper caste people who like the idea of farming and

01:05:20.700 --> 01:05:25.420
[Guest 1]: sarson ke khet and you know, all these lovely things and a village community life, which is

01:05:25.420 --> 01:05:31.740
[Guest 1]: slower and not polluted. They don't know village politics at all. They don't know how bad the caste

01:05:31.740 --> 01:05:36.300
[Amit Varma]: oppression is in villages. In fact, I'd say that, you know, this part of Gandhi's ideology was also

01:05:36.300 --> 01:05:41.500
[Amit Varma]: isomorphic mimicry. He got it from Ruskin and Tolstoy, all of those foreign thinkers who idealized

01:05:41.500 --> 01:05:46.860
[Guest 1]: villages. And Ambedkar pointed out that Gandhi had never lived in a village. You know, he was

01:05:46.860 --> 01:05:51.500
[Guest 1]: born and raised in Porbandar, which was a really important port city. And born to privilege. Born

01:05:51.500 --> 01:05:56.380
[Amit Varma]: in an important family, went abroad, did all of that. Exactly. But romanticize villages, right?

01:05:56.380 --> 01:06:01.260
[Guest 1]: And not this is not because Gandhi's a bad person or ill intention. This is just simply not having

01:06:01.260 --> 01:06:06.460
[Guest 1]: the experience of been in a village and going through caste oppression. Ambedkar, on the other

01:06:06.460 --> 01:06:13.180
[Guest 1]: hand, is not allowed to sit inside the classroom, because he's Dalit, right? He's not given water

01:06:13.180 --> 01:06:19.420
[Guest 1]: that that the other students can get access to because so Ambedkar is very well versed with what

01:06:19.420 --> 01:06:24.940
[Guest 1]: actually happens in a village, especially if you're lower caste and how structural inequity

01:06:24.940 --> 01:06:31.340
[Guest 1]: in a village can cannot go away easily, right? So in that sense, if you think about who is making

01:06:31.340 --> 01:06:36.940
[Guest 1]: policy, it suddenly becomes very important what their experiences, right? The farther away they

01:06:36.940 --> 01:06:42.300
[Guest 1]: are from the median Indian, right, is a really big problem. And the kind of elites we're talking

01:06:42.300 --> 01:06:48.300
[Guest 1]: about are really far away from the median Indian. A second level problem is now if we say that the

01:06:48.300 --> 01:06:52.380
[Guest 1]: most important mandate of government, if you take things like Gandhi's talisman seriously,

01:06:52.940 --> 01:06:56.940
[Guest 1]: is the oppressed Indian, they are not in the same universe as the oppressed Indian,

01:06:56.940 --> 01:07:01.340
[Guest 1]: they've probably never met people from villages, they've never seriously interacted with them,

01:07:01.340 --> 01:07:05.900
[Guest 1]: not because they're not good people, it just simply hasn't happened. Right. So to some extent,

01:07:05.900 --> 01:07:11.180
[Guest 1]: the Indian elite are caste blind, not because caste doesn't exist in India, but because they

01:07:11.180 --> 01:07:15.740
[Guest 1]: haven't encountered it. Or they haven't encountered it viscerally in a lived way.

01:07:15.740 --> 01:07:18.860
[Guest 1]: They might, you know, be intellectually able to sort of talk about it.

01:07:18.860 --> 01:07:23.260
[Guest 1]: Yeah. So Akhil Katyal, who's one of our favorite poets, both Amit and mine,

01:07:23.260 --> 01:07:28.220
[Guest 1]: has a lovely poem, again, I won't dare to quote it exactly. But he talks about how a little boy

01:07:28.220 --> 01:07:33.820
[Guest 1]: about eight years old goes and asks his mother, Mama, what's our caste? And she says, if you

01:07:33.820 --> 01:07:39.660
[Guest 1]: don't know at age eight, it must be upper caste. It must be upper. It must be upper. It's a beautiful

01:07:39.660 --> 01:07:46.540
[Guest 1]: poem. Yeah, so we're caste blind, because it never came up, because we're at the top of the pyramid,

01:07:46.540 --> 01:07:51.260
[Guest 1]: so it doesn't come up. Right. So it really, I don't want to make caste a big issue in terms of

01:07:51.260 --> 01:07:56.780
[Guest 1]: how it informs your economic policy. I'm sure any one of any caste could make excellent economic

01:07:56.780 --> 01:08:04.540
[Guest 1]: policy. But, or bad economic, or bad economic policy, right? So the identity matters, because

01:08:04.540 --> 01:08:10.540
[Guest 1]: the experience matters, and it matters who you're having the conversation with. Now, we have the

01:08:10.540 --> 01:08:15.740
[Guest 1]: most number of elites in finance and economics, because it requires a particular kind of technical

01:08:15.740 --> 01:08:20.540
[Guest 1]: training. Right. And we have some of the best schools, it used to be everyone came back from

01:08:20.540 --> 01:08:26.060
[Guest 1]: the LSE and Oxford and Cambridge, you know, this sort of like Manmohan Singh's generation, IG Patel,

01:08:26.060 --> 01:08:32.060
[Guest 1]: you know, that group of chief economic advisors and finance ministers. We know there's been a

01:08:32.060 --> 01:08:38.380
[Guest 1]: shift to American universities for Indians, you know, the latest crop of advisors, whether it is

01:08:38.380 --> 01:08:43.660
[Guest 1]: Arvind Subramaniam, Arvind Panagaria, Raghuram Rajan, they're all trained in America. So I mean,

01:08:43.660 --> 01:08:47.980
[Amit Varma]: the current local crop is trained in India and defenders of demonetization and frankly,

01:08:47.980 --> 01:08:52.780
[Amit Varma]: bad economists, which is why they are in the positions they are, but let's not go there.

01:08:52.780 --> 01:08:58.860
[Guest 1]: So there is this element of people who have had a particular kind of privilege their whole life,

01:08:58.860 --> 01:09:03.820
[Guest 1]: and they tend to make policies of a particular kind, right? Now, I'm not saying that the

01:09:03.820 --> 01:09:08.300
[Guest 1]: governor of RBI is not thinking about interest rates the right way, because they're elite,

01:09:08.300 --> 01:09:15.340
[Guest 1]: right? That's not the argument. It is that we may not think about demonetization, ATMs, how people

01:09:15.340 --> 01:09:21.820
[Guest 1]: use cash in an economy, what kind of denominations we need to make change when we go to take an

01:09:21.820 --> 01:09:27.180
[Guest 1]: auto rickshaw, those things don't seem to be a priority for the highest level of the RBI,

01:09:27.180 --> 01:09:33.260
[Guest 1]: right? And that part, we need a lot of people at the RBI who are cognizant of how people are

01:09:33.260 --> 01:09:37.740
[Guest 1]: actually using cash in an economy. One of the biggest reasons for the cash crunch post

01:09:37.740 --> 01:09:43.260
[Guest 1]: demonetization was that the new currency that the government introduced was a different size than

01:09:43.260 --> 01:09:46.620
[Guest 1]: the old currency. So the ATMs wouldn't recognize it, right?

01:09:46.620 --> 01:09:47.580
[Amit Varma]: Classic example of

01:09:47.580 --> 01:09:52.700
[Guest 1]: This is a classic example. I mean, this is complete state failure. It's moronic. I mean,

01:09:52.700 --> 01:09:57.660
[Guest 1]: I can't believe that people who are so highly educated actually did execute this policy. But

01:09:57.660 --> 01:10:03.100
[Guest 1]: this is also because at some level, the people at the RBI are not the people who are standing in

01:10:03.100 --> 01:10:07.900
[Guest 1]: line and trying to get cash and trying to make change. They use credit cards, they're the 1%

01:10:07.900 --> 01:10:13.340
[Guest 1]: in India, who are doing credit cards, and they're more worried about cybersecurity and can we get

01:10:13.340 --> 01:10:19.660
[Guest 1]: OTPs, rather than can we get change. So that is where this kind of elitism and privilege really

01:10:19.660 --> 01:10:24.780
[Guest 1]: starts mattering, even with an economic policy. Now you go beyond that, right? Now you talk about

01:10:24.780 --> 01:10:30.460
[Guest 1]: regulation. Now you talk about provision of public goods and services, right? Raghuram Rajan's latest

01:10:30.460 --> 01:10:35.740
[Guest 1]: book has a huge section on how we need to think of the community, right? So this is the third

01:10:35.740 --> 01:10:39.820
[Guest 1]: pillar, right? So we need to bring back the focus on the community. There's a lot of focus on

01:10:39.820 --> 01:10:44.380
[Guest 1]: markets and a lot of focus on the state. We need to think about community seriously and preserving

01:10:45.100 --> 01:10:48.940
[Guest 1]: the great things about community. But there are also some terrible things about Indian

01:10:48.940 --> 01:10:55.100
[Guest 1]: community, right? You live in a village, they never forget who you are, who your grandfather was,

01:10:55.100 --> 01:10:59.500
[Guest 1]: who married whom, what caste you are, did anyone marry out of caste in that particular village?

01:10:59.500 --> 01:11:04.780
[Guest 1]: It's awful. So I think we need more urbanization in India. If you ask any person who lives in a

01:11:04.780 --> 01:11:09.180
[Guest 1]: village, they would want more urbanization in India. But if you asked elites who are thinking

01:11:09.180 --> 01:11:14.140
[Guest 1]: about an American problem, where we need to bring the focus back to the community, because there

01:11:14.140 --> 01:11:19.900
[Guest 1]: are entire communities which are in crisis because of opioid addiction or something like that.

01:11:19.900 --> 01:11:24.780
[Guest 1]: It's not clear to me that that applies one on one to India. And this is not to criticize Raghuram

01:11:24.780 --> 01:11:30.060
[Guest 1]: Rajan. He's a fantastic thinker. I mean, he's a genius. He's the one who predicted the financial

01:11:30.060 --> 01:11:36.140
[Guest 1]: crisis before pretty much anyone else did. But on some of these margins, if someone read Raghuram

01:11:36.140 --> 01:11:40.700
[Guest 1]: Rajan's book and just imported it to India, it would not work at all. It would not work.

01:11:40.700 --> 01:11:46.140
[Amit Varma]: Moving on, you've kind of, you know, described how Indian elites are likely to be English speakers,

01:11:46.140 --> 01:11:50.060
[Amit Varma]: even if they haven't been trained abroad, though many of them have the formative influences are

01:11:50.060 --> 01:11:55.660
[Amit Varma]: likely to be from abroad, not as much lived experiences within the Indian this thing and

01:11:55.660 --> 01:11:59.980
[Amit Varma]: you've given four examples. And I'll, you know, ask you to briefly take us through them four

01:11:59.980 --> 01:12:08.220
[Amit Varma]: examples of recent policies or recent packages of policies, which sort of indicate this sort

01:12:08.220 --> 01:12:14.140
[Amit Varma]: of transplantation of ideas that have worked in the West, but bound to fail in India for,

01:12:14.140 --> 01:12:19.260
[Amit Varma]: you know, reasons of local conditions. Shall we start with maternity leave?

01:12:19.260 --> 01:12:25.740
[Guest 1]: Well, India has one of the best maternity leave policies anywhere in the world. Right? I think

01:12:25.740 --> 01:12:31.180
[Guest 1]: we're almost as good as Sweden and Denmark in terms of how generous the leave is. Right? Now,

01:12:31.180 --> 01:12:35.980
[Guest 1]: there are a few things. This obviously only applies to the formal sector. Right? The second

01:12:35.980 --> 01:12:41.660
[Guest 1]: is Indian female labor force participation is at an all time low, right? It's always been low.

01:12:41.660 --> 01:12:45.420
[Guest 1]: It is particularly low right now for a whole number of reasons. You have a couple of great

01:12:45.420 --> 01:12:51.180
[Amit Varma]: episodes on why so few women with Namita Bhandari and multiple guests, right? And this has something

01:12:51.180 --> 01:12:56.460
[Guest 1]: to do with both the current jobs crisis, where preference is given for the male member of the

01:12:56.460 --> 01:13:02.780
[Guest 1]: family to take the job as opposed to the female member. Second in India, for a lot of a very large

01:13:02.780 --> 01:13:08.940
[Guest 1]: part of India, working women is an inferior good, in the sense that as income levels go up,

01:13:09.820 --> 01:13:14.780
[Guest 1]: you drop out of the labor force, right? This is for most of the country. So I'm again,

01:13:14.780 --> 01:13:20.140
[Guest 1]: one of a very small minority of privileged people that would consider that women should work

01:13:20.140 --> 01:13:26.620
[Guest 1]: because women are equal and so on so forth. For most of India, right? Men and the families think

01:13:26.620 --> 01:13:32.060
[Guest 1]: that the women should work only if it's a dire economic situation. So as soon as the family

01:13:32.060 --> 01:13:36.380
[Guest 1]: or household income starts going up, you know, the women are asked to stay back.

01:13:36.380 --> 01:13:40.220
[Amit Varma]: Which is one of the explanations for the bizarre fact that as India has grown,

01:13:40.220 --> 01:13:42.540
[Amit Varma]: our participation of women in the workforce has gone down.

01:13:42.540 --> 01:13:46.860
[Guest 1]: Exactly, right? So that's so female labor force participation is fairly low.

01:13:47.420 --> 01:13:51.340
[Guest 1]: Now, the second part of female labor force participation is a lot of it is in the

01:13:51.340 --> 01:13:57.100
[Guest 1]: informal sector, right? Most of India operates in the informal sector. We don't have precise

01:13:57.100 --> 01:14:04.140
[Guest 1]: numbers, but estimates put it anywhere like 50 to 70% of the labor force is engaged in the informal

01:14:04.140 --> 01:14:08.860
[Guest 1]: sector, even if they are not themselves vulnerable as informal labor, right? So that's the second

01:14:08.860 --> 01:14:14.940
[Guest 1]: level problem. So we've passed the law, which is first world and first trade, absolutely,

01:14:14.940 --> 01:14:20.860
[Guest 1]: right? And as a young woman myself, and everyone I know who has had children, and I understand the

01:14:20.860 --> 01:14:26.060
[Guest 1]: struggles of, you know, very little maternity leave, and what a luxury that is, it seems like

01:14:26.060 --> 01:14:33.100
[Guest 1]: a great idea, right? But it's going to benefit, maybe a few 1000 women at best, right? But it's

01:14:33.100 --> 01:14:38.140
[Guest 1]: also going to take up state resources in terms of thinking about the law, drafting the law,

01:14:38.140 --> 01:14:43.500
[Guest 1]: enforcing the law, right? Who are the kinds of firms who are likely to give this kind of

01:14:43.500 --> 01:14:48.940
[Guest 1]: maternity leave, they're going to be the top end firms, right? This is like the law firms or the

01:14:48.940 --> 01:14:55.340
[Guest 1]: top end businesses who are likely to just through social change and peer pressure, very likely to

01:14:55.340 --> 01:15:00.220
[Guest 1]: adopt good maternity leave policies, because otherwise they would lose these women who are

01:15:00.220 --> 01:15:05.900
[Guest 1]: so gifted, operating at the highest level of the Indian economy, right? Any firm lower than that,

01:15:06.780 --> 01:15:11.740
[Guest 1]: either the law doesn't apply to or it won't be enforced, which means it doesn't matter, right?

01:15:11.740 --> 01:15:16.380
[Guest 2]: And to the extent that it is enforced, it just raises costs raises the cost of hiring women

01:15:16.380 --> 01:15:21.420
[Guest 2]: can even backfire and make it more costly to hire women. So you hire fewer women.

01:15:21.420 --> 01:15:25.580
[Amit Varma]: In fact, when I was editing Pragati, I'd, you know, published a paper, I think by Devika Kher,

01:15:25.580 --> 01:15:30.860
[Amit Varma]: I don't remember who, an article about how this has actually affected the employment of women,

01:15:30.860 --> 01:15:35.820
[Amit Varma]: because firms are now incentivized to hire men instead of women when there are equivalent

01:15:35.820 --> 01:15:39.340
[Amit Varma]: candidates. So the incentives are terrible, which is what the coercive power of the state can

01:15:39.340 --> 01:15:43.740
[Amit Varma]: sometimes do with these unintended consequences. And you quoted Anthony Allard's great phrase,

01:15:43.740 --> 01:15:48.460
[Guest 2]: phantom legislation. Yes, yeah, exactly. I mean, it's a phantom legislation. And again,

01:15:48.460 --> 01:15:52.300
[Amit Varma]: it's another example of virtue signaling. And phantom legislation, just to define it being

01:15:52.300 --> 01:15:56.700
[Amit Varma]: the passing of laws, which do not have, and most probably cannot have the desired effect.

01:15:56.700 --> 01:16:02.780
[Guest 2]: Yeah, it's laws which are on the books and which you can point to your friends. And so when this

01:16:02.780 --> 01:16:07.740
[Guest 2]: law was passed, the Labor Minister, you know, very proudly said, you know, we have a maternity

01:16:07.740 --> 01:16:12.860
[Guest 2]: leave law, you know, as good as that in Sweden. And yet, when you think about that, that's a bizarre,

01:16:12.860 --> 01:16:21.980
[Guest 2]: that's a bizarre thing to be proud of. You know, India does not need and probably should not have

01:16:22.620 --> 01:16:28.940
[Guest 2]: the same laws as Sweden does. I mean, that is, if India adopted all the laws of Sweden,

01:16:28.940 --> 01:16:35.980
[Guest 2]: it would be a complete disaster. So this is kind of a bizarre thing to be proud of. And

01:16:35.980 --> 01:16:41.900
[Guest 2]: as Shruti points out, it doesn't apply to most women. And most women have problems,

01:16:41.900 --> 01:16:48.460
[Guest 2]: which are far, far greater than maternity leave. I mean, you know, let's talk about,

01:16:48.460 --> 01:16:53.820
[Guest 2]: you know, violence against women, or let's talk about, you know, getting basic health care. How

01:16:53.820 --> 01:16:59.500
[Guest 2]: about how far you have to walk to get water? That's an issue which affects women. How far do

01:16:59.500 --> 01:17:05.420
[Guest 2]: you have to walk to get water? Not maternity leave. I mean, the idea that this is something

01:17:05.420 --> 01:17:12.940
[Guest 2]: which one should broadcast to the world, when a millions of people are walking huge distances in

01:17:12.940 --> 01:17:19.020
[Guest 2]: unbearable heat to get water for their families. There's such a huge disconnect between the law

01:17:19.020 --> 01:17:23.260
[Guest 2]: that you pass and are proud of and tell your friends in the liberal community, in the

01:17:23.260 --> 01:17:28.780
[Guest 2]: international community, and the reality on the ground is just bizarre. So this probably came

01:17:28.780 --> 01:17:34.620
[Guest 1]: about, I mean, if I were to hazard a guess, because elite policymakers saw their friends

01:17:34.620 --> 01:17:39.660
[Guest 1]: who are probably women like me, right, at my age, they're working at law firms, they're working at

01:17:39.660 --> 01:17:44.860
[Guest 1]: the top blue chip firms in India. And they got, you know, very little maternity leave, and they

01:17:44.860 --> 01:17:49.820
[Guest 1]: didn't have much negotiating power. And they said, we must fix this with a law. That's probably what

01:17:49.820 --> 01:17:56.460
[Guest 1]: happened. But the reality is, in India, one of two things happen. If the families have a certain

01:17:56.460 --> 01:18:02.540
[Guest 1]: income level, the moment a woman is pregnant, there is no question that she would work at all,

01:18:02.540 --> 01:18:07.900
[Guest 1]: right? It's just out of question. And if a woman is of a certain income level where she can't afford

01:18:08.460 --> 01:18:13.740
[Guest 1]: this luxury of taking time off, when she's pregnant, she's pretty much working till the

01:18:13.740 --> 01:18:18.860
[Guest 1]: day the baby is born. And you can just see this if you look at all the domestic help,

01:18:18.860 --> 01:18:25.820
[Guest 1]: right? Most domestic help in India works until maybe the last week or so before the baby is

01:18:25.820 --> 01:18:31.820
[Guest 1]: delivered. Right? And domestic work is not easy work. I hope that the people employing them go

01:18:31.820 --> 01:18:36.540
[Guest 1]: easy on them in the last few months. And I'm sure there's some social system that looks after,

01:18:37.180 --> 01:18:42.540
[Guest 1]: you know, pregnant women in its own bizarre way. But it simply doesn't apply to those women,

01:18:42.540 --> 01:18:50.780
[Guest 1]: right? So we're not helping anyone, except a few 1000 women who already have a lot of privilege,

01:18:51.580 --> 01:18:56.700
[Guest 1]: and a fair amount of leverage in terms of being able to negotiate greater amounts of leave and

01:18:56.700 --> 01:19:01.660
[Guest 1]: things like that. And that's not a bad aim in itself. I'm not saying we should help no women,

01:19:01.660 --> 01:19:06.700
[Guest 1]: it's just that it does clog up state capacity, right? Those are the women who will file suit

01:19:06.700 --> 01:19:12.620
[Guest 1]: in a court, and it were this rule not to be followed or not to be enforced. Right? This

01:19:12.620 --> 01:19:17.420
[Guest 1]: took up time in terms of drafting the policy, framing the policy, passing it in Parliament,

01:19:17.420 --> 01:19:22.700
[Guest 1]: having debate and discussion on how to enforce it, creating like an enforcement mechanism.

01:19:22.700 --> 01:19:26.940
[Guest 1]: All of this took up state capacity. And the argument is not that it's it's not a good thing

01:19:26.940 --> 01:19:36.220
[Guest 1]: to have, it's that we have far greater problems, right to solve for most of our women. And I think

01:19:36.220 --> 01:19:42.220
[Guest 1]: those are the things like every government needs to prioritize. And this screws up the priority

01:19:42.220 --> 01:19:46.860
[Amit Varma]: scheme. And again, I'd like to sort of emphasize, you know, people often give this common response

01:19:46.860 --> 01:19:51.580
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, we should do everything. It's not either or we should do them all. And the point is

01:19:51.580 --> 01:19:57.420
[Amit Varma]: wake up, that's not possible. Our state capacity is incredibly limited. Everything you do is at

01:19:57.420 --> 01:20:02.460
[Amit Varma]: the cost of something else. And therefore, like you said, Shruti, we have to prioritize on whether

01:20:02.460 --> 01:20:07.500
[Amit Varma]: we want to do things which the elites feel good about, or whether we want to actually go down and

01:20:07.500 --> 01:20:11.900
[Amit Varma]: examine the real problems of the country and do something about that. Yeah, you have to prioritize.

01:20:11.900 --> 01:20:16.860
[Guest 2]: And not only that, but I think you have to learn state capacity is not something which you simply

01:20:16.860 --> 01:20:22.380
[Guest 2]: have or don't have. It's something which builds, which develops over time. So when people see that

01:20:22.380 --> 01:20:27.980
[Guest 2]: the state is successful, then the state could be more successful in the future. So when you have

01:20:27.980 --> 01:20:33.340
[Guest 2]: that the state is failing or flailing on all grounds, then people don't pay attention to it.

01:20:33.340 --> 01:20:38.220
[Guest 2]: And it becomes very difficult for the state to be successful, even at the few things it should

01:20:38.220 --> 01:20:43.660
[Guest 2]: be doing. So state capacity is something which needs to build over time. And the way you do that

01:20:43.660 --> 01:20:48.460
[Guest 2]: is you start with the most important things and you actually do those things and enforce those

01:20:48.460 --> 01:20:54.220
[Guest 2]: things and do those things seriously, as India can. I mean, India has done this with its voting

01:20:54.220 --> 01:21:00.860
[Guest 2]: system, its democratic system. Where India decides this is important, this is a priority, it can and

01:21:00.860 --> 01:21:06.140
[Guest 2]: it does. We're talking about the Delhi Metro, which by the way, is great. I mean, the Delhi

01:21:06.140 --> 01:21:11.740
[Guest 2]: Metro actually, it does work. I like it. It's a good thing that it can be done. But there are

01:21:11.740 --> 01:21:18.060
[Guest 2]: limited resources, there are always trade-offs, you can't do everything. So you need to prioritize

01:21:18.060 --> 01:21:24.300
[Guest 2]: and then people begin to respect the state and then the state can grow and do these other things.

01:21:24.300 --> 01:21:26.220
[Guest 1]: SHIKRITI TRIPATHI Yeah. And this is where

01:21:26.220 --> 01:21:32.060
[Guest 1]: one reason we talk so much about the characteristics of elites is that their priorities are determined

01:21:32.060 --> 01:21:37.900
[Guest 1]: by where they are looking to, which tends to be the West, right? And this is where representation

01:21:37.900 --> 01:21:44.140
[Guest 1]: matters, not because you and I as Savarnas can speak about caste, it's the only thing we are

01:21:44.140 --> 01:21:50.700
[Guest 1]: saying about caste is we need more representation of all castes while we are making this kind of

01:21:50.700 --> 01:21:55.580
[Guest 1]: policy. We need more representation of people who speak languages that are different from English,

01:21:55.580 --> 01:22:00.780
[Guest 1]: while we are making these policies. Same for women. I don't think anyone asked any survey of

01:22:00.780 --> 01:22:06.380
[Guest 1]: the median women in India, if maternity leave is a big problem. And they would have said maternity

01:22:06.380 --> 01:22:13.100
[Guest 1]: leave what? Right? So that's what we mean by the elites look outwards, not because they're bad

01:22:13.100 --> 01:22:18.300
[Guest 1]: people, because that's the world they inhibit. And that world that they inhibit is fantasy,

01:22:18.300 --> 01:22:22.940
[Guest 1]: as far as most of India is concerned. Most of India just lives in a completely different space.

01:22:22.940 --> 01:22:27.980
[Guest 1]: And we have had made no effort to get greater representation of what it means to live in that

01:22:27.980 --> 01:22:33.260
[Amit Varma]: space. Right? So we have only about 40 minutes left. So I suspect I am the only podcaster who

01:22:33.260 --> 01:22:39.260
[Amit Varma]: will say only about 40 minutes left. But we have only about 40 minutes left. So what I will sort of

01:22:39.260 --> 01:22:45.260
[Amit Varma]: try to do here is, let's go over your three other case studies in about five to seven minutes each.

01:22:45.260 --> 01:22:50.060
[Amit Varma]: So we can then discuss the larger sort of questions at hand and kind of wrap it up. Now,

01:22:50.060 --> 01:22:54.700
[Amit Varma]: housing regulation is something you speak about in your paper. We've all had multiple episodes on

01:22:54.700 --> 01:23:00.300
[Amit Varma]: this. It was from you, Alex, that when we did an episode on FSI together that I learned that great

01:23:00.300 --> 01:23:05.180
[Amit Varma]: phrase that where you said that Bombay should stop reclaiming the sea, we should reclaim the sky

01:23:05.180 --> 01:23:10.300
[Amit Varma]: and build upwards, which was very eloquent. And, and from Shruti, I got sort of that

01:23:10.300 --> 01:23:14.780
[Amit Varma]: amazing TIL moment in the episode on 12 dream reforms, where you pointed out that

01:23:14.780 --> 01:23:18.940
[Amit Varma]: one of the most powerful forms of mass transport is the elevator.

01:23:18.940 --> 01:23:21.900
[Guest 1]: I got that from Tim Harford. I can't take credit for that.

01:23:21.900 --> 01:23:28.460
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So Tim Harford, Bastia Prize winners for the win. And we shall. So tell me a little bit

01:23:28.460 --> 01:23:32.860
[Amit Varma]: about how so many of our housing regulations, you know, designed in an earlier colonial era,

01:23:32.860 --> 01:23:35.740
[Guest 2]: where people are elites are sprawling bungalows around that.

01:23:35.740 --> 01:23:40.860
[Guest 2]: Yeah. So the regulations date to the colonial era, where the British wanted to recreate

01:23:40.860 --> 01:23:47.020
[Guest 2]: New England, that is the old England, you know, and have these bungalows. And in the bungalow,

01:23:47.020 --> 01:23:53.500
[Guest 2]: you have a nice garden and you have, you know, a big distance between the driveway and the street

01:23:53.500 --> 01:23:59.580
[Guest 2]: and the front door and so forth, and space for your car, right? This became later, it's car,

01:23:59.580 --> 01:24:03.740
[Guest 2]: important to have space for car. But when you think about what India really needs,

01:24:03.740 --> 01:24:08.380
[Guest 2]: most Indians don't have cars, they have motorcycles or they have bikes or something like that.

01:24:08.380 --> 01:24:15.580
[Guest 2]: So every use of space, which you put to cars, which you put to lawns, which you put to having

01:24:15.580 --> 01:24:20.940
[Guest 2]: a big distance between the front door of the house and the street, all that means is you're

01:24:20.940 --> 01:24:27.420
[Guest 2]: raising the cost of housing. That land is expensive. If you use land for a lawn, that is

01:24:28.140 --> 01:24:33.660
[Guest 2]: land which is not being used to actually house people. So all of these regulations,

01:24:33.660 --> 01:24:41.020
[Guest 2]: which were designed to create a English bungalow style living, don't apply to the way that Indians

01:24:41.020 --> 01:24:48.140
[Guest 2]: actually live. And this means raises the cost of providing housing for real Indians and means that,

01:24:48.140 --> 01:24:57.100
[Guest 2]: ironically, the only truly free market in housing in India is the slums. And the slums in that sense

01:24:57.100 --> 01:25:04.700
[Guest 2]: actually work quite well. The slums are not ideal, but they are an amazing response to terrible

01:25:04.700 --> 01:25:10.860
[Guest 2]: regulation. So the government, you know, could go and provide housing, so-called affordable housing,

01:25:10.860 --> 01:25:16.220
[Guest 2]: but where do they put it? They put it where land is cheap outside the city and where it's very

01:25:16.220 --> 01:25:20.860
[Guest 2]: difficult to get to work. And so people respond and say, no, I'd actually prefer to live in the

01:25:20.860 --> 01:25:26.620
[Guest 2]: slums, which are closer to where work is. So the slums are actually responsive to people's real

01:25:26.620 --> 01:25:32.300
[Guest 2]: needs. The problem is that they're not provided with government services like water and electricity

01:25:32.300 --> 01:25:38.780
[Guest 2]: and sewage. So this is another case where we have premature imitation. We have regulations in order

01:25:38.780 --> 01:25:44.460
[Guest 2]: to create British style bungalow living. And at the same time, the state fails on its primary

01:25:44.460 --> 01:25:52.060
[Guest 2]: duties. You know, as I said, sewage, electricity and water. So this is the big disconnect.

01:25:52.060 --> 01:25:58.940
[Amit Varma]: No, and it also strikes me that, you know, slums are an excellent example of society's solution to

01:25:58.940 --> 01:26:03.180
[Amit Varma]: a problem created by the state, you know, and they are demonized. And for example, you know,

01:26:03.180 --> 01:26:07.420
[Amit Varma]: the informal sector is demonized. The informal sector is also society's solution to a problem

01:26:07.420 --> 01:26:10.620
[Amit Varma]: created by the state and they're unfairly demonized. I had an episode on slums a long

01:26:10.620 --> 01:26:15.820
[Amit Varma]: time back with Pawan Srinath where he pointed out that slums are so essential to cities because they

01:26:15.820 --> 01:26:22.060
[Amit Varma]: allow a cheap entry point for migration into cities, which people often forget.

01:26:22.060 --> 01:26:26.140
[Guest 1]: Yeah. And you know, the second aspect of the kind of housing regulation we have and

01:26:26.140 --> 01:26:31.580
[Guest 1]: Alain Berto's Order Without Design, it's a great, great book. Doesn't just talk about this happening

01:26:31.580 --> 01:26:35.820
[Guest 1]: in India, but all over the world, everywhere regulators from New York City, you know,

01:26:35.820 --> 01:26:41.820
[Guest 1]: further down. The regulators tend to be elite and they think about how people should live

01:26:42.460 --> 01:26:48.860
[Guest 1]: and not how people actually live. So they think in terms of, you know, any civilized person should

01:26:48.860 --> 01:26:54.940
[Guest 1]: have so many square meters of living space, which means the smallest size one bedroom you can make

01:26:54.940 --> 01:27:00.300
[Guest 1]: is X number of square meters, right? The smallest two bedroom you make for a family is X number of

01:27:00.300 --> 01:27:05.900
[Guest 1]: square meters. Most Indian families don't give a separate, you know, set of bedrooms to their kids,

01:27:06.700 --> 01:27:12.460
[Guest 1]: right? Most Indian families at particular income groups, there's one room and everything happens

01:27:12.460 --> 01:27:16.620
[Guest 1]: in that one room and in the evening when all sort of your living room activities are done,

01:27:16.620 --> 01:27:21.500
[Guest 1]: you pull out the gada, you spread it and now it's the bedroom for the night, right? This is how a

01:27:21.500 --> 01:27:26.780
[Guest 1]: lot of us grew up. This is how most of Bombay functions, right? Even at higher levels of income.

01:27:26.780 --> 01:27:32.060
[Guest 1]: So a regulator coming in and telling people how they should live and how they should use their

01:27:32.060 --> 01:27:38.060
[Guest 1]: space is really bizarre as opposed to asking, how do people actually use their space, right? How do

01:27:38.060 --> 01:27:44.380
[Guest 1]: you use that extra space outside, which is the gap between the building and the road? And in Bombay,

01:27:44.380 --> 01:27:48.860
[Guest 1]: they've lent it out to panvalas, they've lent it out to people who do the ironing right inside the

01:27:48.860 --> 01:27:53.900
[Guest 1]: society gate. This is because that space is valuable. It needs to be used. We put it there

01:27:53.900 --> 01:27:59.820
[Guest 1]: as empty space only because of bad regulation, right? So these are things to consider in terms

01:27:59.820 --> 01:28:05.900
[Guest 1]: of regulators, thinking about how people actually live as opposed to how we want them to live. Now,

01:28:05.900 --> 01:28:11.180
[Guest 1]: nobody wants to live in a slum, but if you go to a slum, it will tell us a lot about what people

01:28:11.180 --> 01:28:17.340
[Guest 1]: prioritize. They prioritize distance from work, even over having sewage, right? They prioritize

01:28:17.340 --> 01:28:22.060
[Guest 1]: that their kids can go to a good school nearby and that the mother can drop the kids off at school,

01:28:22.060 --> 01:28:27.340
[Guest 1]: go do her work, pick up the kids from school and come back home. Same problems mothers have in

01:28:27.340 --> 01:28:32.620
[Guest 1]: Arlington and Fairfax, where Alex and I live, right? Same kind of issues that mothers have in

01:28:32.620 --> 01:28:38.060
[Guest 1]: slums. That's why distance really matters. So they're willing to give up piped water delivery

01:28:38.620 --> 01:28:43.900
[Guest 1]: in exchange for that. And the only reason those poor people are forced to make that trade-off

01:28:43.900 --> 01:28:50.220
[Guest 1]: is because we haven't provided for regulation, which will allow for really tiny, small living

01:28:50.220 --> 01:28:56.060
[Guest 1]: spaces, which are, you know, regulated, right, formal sector spaces, because we think that's

01:28:56.060 --> 01:29:00.540
[Amit Varma]: too small for a human to inhabit. You know, my listeners often ask me for book recommendations.

01:29:00.540 --> 01:29:04.780
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, what you just said reminds me of two masterpieces I'll recommend. One is a book

01:29:04.780 --> 01:29:10.060
[Amit Varma]: called The Power Broker by Robert Caro about Robert Moses, a man who built New York, which is

01:29:10.060 --> 01:29:15.340
[Amit Varma]: a magnificent biography, not just of a man, but of the corrosive influence of power on individuals

01:29:15.340 --> 01:29:20.220
[Amit Varma]: and also of a city. And Moses did everything exactly wrong, you know, top down planning,

01:29:20.220 --> 01:29:24.940
[Amit Varma]: coercive state power, and so on. And the other book is a lady who opposed him, Jane Jacobs,

01:29:24.940 --> 01:29:28.780
[Amit Varma]: who wrote this incredible book called The Death and Life of Great American Cities,

01:29:28.780 --> 01:29:35.260
[Amit Varma]: which argues for and makes a case for allowing cities to organically evolve. And, you know,

01:29:35.260 --> 01:29:40.620
[Amit Varma]: within their own local constraints and expressing its own local character, which are both

01:29:40.620 --> 01:29:44.860
[Guest 1]: masterpieces. Speaking of Jane Jacobs, I think Alain Bertaud's book is perfect to complete that

01:29:44.860 --> 01:29:49.660
[Guest 1]: trilogy. He's an actual masterpiece as well. All linked from the show notes. One of the things he

01:29:49.660 --> 01:29:54.780
[Guest 1]: talks about in the book specifically about Mumbai is about how we haven't created circumstances

01:29:54.780 --> 01:29:58.780
[Guest 1]: where you can easily change land use from one kind of use to another kind of use, which is

01:29:58.780 --> 01:30:05.980
[Guest 1]: critical to a city, right? So we have had mill land in the center of the city, right? Thousands

01:30:05.980 --> 01:30:10.700
[Guest 1]: of acres of mill land completely tied up. And now what do you have in those mill lands? You have,

01:30:10.700 --> 01:30:16.540
[Guest 1]: you know, posh cafes with paper straws is what you have on mill land these days, because we simply

01:30:16.540 --> 01:30:22.300
[Guest 1]: did not convert the land use from industrial to commercial and then commercial to residential or

01:30:22.300 --> 01:30:28.140
[Guest 1]: some form of that, which means now the center of Mumbai is no longer valuable, right? All the

01:30:28.140 --> 01:30:32.860
[Guest 1]: business hubs are either in the south end of Mumbai, or a little bit further north near,

01:30:32.860 --> 01:30:38.460
[Guest 1]: you know, BKC. Because, and this is a direct consequence of not allowing,

01:30:38.460 --> 01:30:43.740
[Guest 1]: right, Verley and those neighboring areas, which had lots of mills, to properly change land use

01:30:43.740 --> 01:30:48.860
[Guest 1]: when the mill shut down. So this is a really big problem when the government says we must have

01:30:48.860 --> 01:30:54.140
[Guest 1]: industrial use in the middle of Bombay, which is the most valuable real estate, perhaps anywhere

01:30:54.140 --> 01:30:59.340
[Guest 1]: in the world. So we have bad regulation, right? And we have bad regulation, because they once

01:30:59.340 --> 01:31:05.340
[Guest 1]: again read books by people like Robert Moses, on, you know, stratifying cities, the way Moses

01:31:05.340 --> 01:31:09.020
[Guest 1]: think they're supposed to look, as opposed to how cities actually operate. And of course,

01:31:09.020 --> 01:31:12.540
[Amit Varma]: there's an engineering mindset at play as well, where you want to design everything,

01:31:12.540 --> 01:31:16.460
[Amit Varma]: not realizing some things are too complex to be designed. The next example is...

01:31:16.460 --> 01:31:20.700
[Guest 1]: One last thing, speaking of elite imitation, the person one we must really read on Indian

01:31:20.700 --> 01:31:25.980
[Guest 1]: housing regulation is Bimal Patel. Yeah, right. Yeah. So in typical elite imitation format,

01:31:25.980 --> 01:31:30.380
[Guest 1]: we've talked about Jane Jacobs, and we've talked about Elian Bhatto. But the person who actually

01:31:30.380 --> 01:31:36.060
[Guest 1]: dissects Indian housing policy, what are the rules, the way they actually are written in India,

01:31:36.060 --> 01:31:40.380
[Guest 1]: and the way they actually work, and the unintended consequences of that, that is Bimal Patel. And,

01:31:40.380 --> 01:31:42.780
[Guest 1]: you know, all his fantastic work. We cite a bunch of it in the paper.

01:31:42.780 --> 01:31:50.540
[Guest 2]: This is making win-win solutions actually work in Amitabh. So he is an extremely important person

01:31:50.540 --> 01:31:57.740
[Guest 2]: in the Indian context, who is finding ways, bringing the farmers in, bringing the industrialists,

01:31:57.740 --> 01:32:02.940
[Guest 2]: the developers in, and making sure that everybody gets a piece of the pie. And that is actually the

01:32:02.940 --> 01:32:07.980
[Guest 2]: way for India to develop. Because another, you know, very closely related problem is the ridiculous

01:32:09.100 --> 01:32:16.540
[Guest 2]: difficulty it is for farmers to sell their land to non-farm use. You know, we perhaps do this in

01:32:16.540 --> 01:32:20.940
[Guest 2]: order to, quote, protect the farmers, right? Another example of the elites thinking that they

01:32:20.940 --> 01:32:26.060
[Guest 2]: must protect the farmers. But in fact, the land is some of the farmers' most valuable assets.

01:32:26.060 --> 01:32:33.420
[Guest 2]: And if you can't turn it into a developable land, you are destroying the value of that asset.

01:32:33.420 --> 01:32:36.380
[Amit Varma]: This is what Hanan wrote this auto called debt capital, though again,

01:32:36.380 --> 01:32:40.780
[Amit Varma]: I'm showing elite imitation by even citing this auto. But yeah, conceptually,

01:32:40.780 --> 01:32:44.860
[Amit Varma]: that's extremely useful. Let's kind of move on to open defecation, which is a third case study,

01:32:44.860 --> 01:32:49.340
[Amit Varma]: which of course we have, you know, Shruti and I have done a long episode on Swachh Bharat,

01:32:49.340 --> 01:32:53.500
[Amit Varma]: and I'd encourage you to listen to that. Do you want to quickly sum up in just a couple of lines

01:32:53.500 --> 01:32:58.940
[Guest 1]: what? Yeah, we need to focus on waste management solutions and not on toilets, right? Toilet is

01:32:58.940 --> 01:33:05.500
[Guest 1]: just one step. It's the last mile step in how we think about waste management in India. Now,

01:33:05.500 --> 01:33:09.980
[Guest 1]: because of the way we are culturally and in particular, because of caste relations and

01:33:09.980 --> 01:33:17.260
[Guest 1]: ritual purity, most Indian caste groups, the Savarnas, and even a large number of the Dalit

01:33:17.260 --> 01:33:24.780
[Guest 1]: groups refuse to have anything to do with human excreta and feces, right? So if you create a

01:33:24.780 --> 01:33:30.540
[Guest 1]: system where people have to use toilets and then manually empty them or empty them using a vacuum

01:33:30.540 --> 01:33:36.940
[Guest 1]: or in any way have to deal with it, it is going to have a very big consequence on caste. Most

01:33:36.940 --> 01:33:42.620
[Guest 1]: upper caste people simply won't adopt it. And the more number of people that adopted there's a huge

01:33:42.620 --> 01:33:50.380
[Guest 1]: aspect of oppression because it re-enables or revitalizes this awful practice of manual scavenging

01:33:50.380 --> 01:33:56.300
[Guest 1]: and things like that that we outlawed a long time ago. So we have created a Swachh Bharat Abhiyan

01:33:56.300 --> 01:34:01.660
[Guest 1]: which translates to cleaner India, right? We want a cleaner India, but we're only talking about

01:34:01.660 --> 01:34:08.220
[Guest 1]: cleaner India in terms of toilet, right? So what we did was the entire focus was on building toilets

01:34:08.220 --> 01:34:13.660
[Guest 1]: and delivering toilets to every household without understanding how they actually go about their

01:34:13.660 --> 01:34:16.700
[Guest 1]: business, right? So do they want to use...

01:34:16.700 --> 01:34:20.620
[Guest 2]: The elites sort of naturally think that the problem of open defecation is that there aren't

01:34:20.620 --> 01:34:27.180
[Guest 2]: enough toilets because who would possibly want to defecate in the open if they had a toilet?

01:34:27.180 --> 01:34:29.100
[Guest 2]: But in fact, that's not the case.

01:34:29.100 --> 01:34:36.060
[Guest 1]: Because elites, for elites, toilets come in a great package deal included with excellent sewage

01:34:36.060 --> 01:34:42.700
[Guest 1]: solution and piped water, right? So when I think of a toilet, I'm thinking of a package deal.

01:34:42.700 --> 01:34:46.780
[Guest 1]: The kind of toilet that Swachh Bharat Abhiyan is giving out is just the toilet.

01:34:46.780 --> 01:34:49.740
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't come with piped water. It doesn't come with sewage.

01:34:49.740 --> 01:34:53.420
[Amit Varma]: That's why I think of it as an excellent illustration of, you know, how some governments

01:34:53.420 --> 01:34:58.140
[Amit Varma]: focus more on optics than actual governance. So the toilet is great optics. It's what you see,

01:34:58.140 --> 01:35:02.700
[Amit Varma]: but you need a drainage system below that. And what you pointed out in your paper and in the

01:35:02.700 --> 01:35:08.220
[Amit Varma]: episode that we did, is that if you don't have the drainage system, then people either have to

01:35:08.220 --> 01:35:12.780
[Amit Varma]: clean it themselves, which they consider a quote unquote, Dalit activity, and they don't want to

01:35:12.780 --> 01:35:18.220
[Amit Varma]: do it. Or they have to actually get a Dalit into the house to do it. And therefore, even beyond

01:35:18.220 --> 01:35:23.340
[Amit Varma]: this issue of caste and ritual cleansing, there are all kinds of cultural issues for why people

01:35:24.780 --> 01:35:30.460
[Amit Varma]: prefer open defecation. And and therefore it, you know, this is a classic example of what sounds

01:35:30.460 --> 01:35:34.620
[Amit Varma]: like a great policy to the elites, but hey, think a little deeper, literally.

01:35:34.620 --> 01:35:40.060
[Guest 2]: Yeah, no, I will say that, even though the policy might not have been, you know,

01:35:40.060 --> 01:35:45.020
[Guest 2]: exactly perfect for the problem was a very good thing that Modi pointed attention to this problem.

01:35:45.020 --> 01:35:49.980
[Guest 2]: Yeah, because it's a serious problem. It's one which in another country might have been

01:35:49.980 --> 01:35:52.540
[Guest 2]: hidden away, right? Nobody wants to talk about it. Nobody wants to talk about it,

01:35:52.540 --> 01:35:57.900
[Guest 2]: but he talked about it. So I got to give him credit for talking about defecation. I mean,

01:35:57.900 --> 01:36:03.420
[Guest 2]: this is something which is not comfortable to bring up, but he made it a priority. And I think

01:36:03.420 --> 01:36:09.500
[Guest 2]: overall, it's probably done some good because we have to also remember that open defecation kills

01:36:09.500 --> 01:36:15.100
[Guest 2]: people because it creates a huge amount of bacteria in the environment. It kills children.

01:36:15.100 --> 01:36:19.980
[Guest 2]: It stunts children. It creates, you know, the possibilities for cholera and things of that

01:36:19.980 --> 01:36:26.380
[Guest 2]: nature. So I do think that even though the solution was not exactly pointing to the right

01:36:26.380 --> 01:36:30.780
[Guest 2]: issues, just talking about it was a very big deal. Just to sort of drive that home. I had the

01:36:30.780 --> 01:36:35.020
[Amit Varma]: Congress politician, the very fine economist Salman Sohz on my show. And at the end, I threw

01:36:35.020 --> 01:36:39.020
[Amit Varma]: him what I thought was a googly that why don't you say something good about Mr. Modi. And he said

01:36:39.020 --> 01:36:46.140
[Amit Varma]: precisely this. He said that a man in a position of that much influence can really change the minds

01:36:46.140 --> 01:36:50.860
[Amit Varma]: of a lot of people on issues. So just by talking about Swachh Bharat, even if you don't actually

01:36:50.860 --> 01:36:55.500
[Amit Varma]: make that kind of difference on the ground because of implementation issues, or your policy is badly

01:36:55.500 --> 01:37:02.380
[Guest 1]: designed, can make a difference to the culture. And of course, I want to point out one thing,

01:37:03.580 --> 01:37:11.020
[Guest 1]: which is related to the elite imitation. They tied up the outcome of Swachh Bharat

01:37:11.020 --> 01:37:17.740
[Guest 1]: to delivering toilets, right. So on October 2, on the 150th birth anniversary of Gandhi,

01:37:17.740 --> 01:37:22.940
[Guest 1]: Modi had set a target that, you know, by 2019, India will be open defecation free,

01:37:22.940 --> 01:37:27.180
[Guest 1]: and they declared India open defecation free, when in fact, India is nowhere close to open

01:37:27.180 --> 01:37:32.460
[Guest 1]: defecation free. It's definitely improved, as Alex pointed out. But the reason that the government

01:37:32.460 --> 01:37:37.420
[Guest 1]: has declared it so, it's because they met the target of how many toilets needed to be given

01:37:37.420 --> 01:37:40.860
[Guest 1]: to how many households. And they said, Oh, we've solved the problem, right?

01:37:40.860 --> 01:37:41.740
[Guest 1]: Mission accomplished.

01:37:41.740 --> 01:37:42.300
[Guest 1]: Mission accomplished.

01:37:43.660 --> 01:37:52.700
[Guest 1]: Exactly. So now, it's a bizarre thing, where we have conflated input with outcomes,

01:37:52.700 --> 01:37:57.980
[Guest 1]: right. And this is another virtue of, you know, in other places, had we given people toilets,

01:37:57.980 --> 01:38:02.540
[Guest 1]: they would have used them, right, either because the sewage and the water exists,

01:38:02.540 --> 01:38:07.420
[Guest 1]: or because none of this caste and ritual purity nonsense, you know, none of that exists,

01:38:07.420 --> 01:38:12.460
[Guest 1]: right. But here we have those problems. So if you conflate the input with the outcome,

01:38:12.460 --> 01:38:14.300
[Guest 1]: then you are going to get a lot of shit.

01:38:14.300 --> 01:38:17.260
[Amit Varma]: In fact, conflating input with outcome is exactly what you know,

01:38:17.260 --> 01:38:21.900
[Amit Varma]: ails our education system. And your fourth case was, you know, about the Right to Education Act,

01:38:21.900 --> 01:38:25.900
[Amit Varma]: which was a massive disaster. I've had episodes on that. And you've written about it very well

01:38:25.900 --> 01:38:29.980
[Amit Varma]: in your paper, which I will encourage all my listeners to go and read because we are moving

01:38:29.980 --> 01:38:35.820
[Amit Varma]: on from that. And I'd rather like to sort of come to your conclusion, which is that limited state

01:38:35.820 --> 01:38:42.140
[Amit Varma]: capacity calls for presumptive laissez faire. And I'll quote from your paper. Imagine, for example,

01:38:42.140 --> 01:38:46.620
[Amit Varma]: that US government spending had to be cut by a factor of 10. Would it make sense to cut all

01:38:46.620 --> 01:38:52.140
[Amit Varma]: programs by 90%? Unlikely. Some programs and policies are of great value, but others should

01:38:52.140 --> 01:38:57.660
[Amit Varma]: be undertaken only when state capacity and GDP per capita are higher. And then he gives Edward

01:38:57.660 --> 01:39:03.740
[Amit Varma]: laser quote, which you gave earlier. And then you guys say, a US government funded at one 10th,

01:39:03.740 --> 01:39:08.460
[Amit Varma]: the current level would optimally do many fewer things. So why doesn't the Indian government do

01:39:08.460 --> 01:39:12.940
[Amit Varma]: many fewer things? Stop good. You know, a lot of people will instinctively react to this saying

01:39:12.940 --> 01:39:16.620
[Amit Varma]: that, hey, we need the government because the market doesn't do all of these things properly.

01:39:16.620 --> 01:39:20.540
[Amit Varma]: But the issue there is that usually a the government is creating problems, which then

01:39:20.540 --> 01:39:25.740
[Amit Varma]: society comes and find this own solutions to the market like slums, like informal markets,

01:39:25.740 --> 01:39:30.860
[Amit Varma]: and be people are very keen to spot market failure, not realizing that government failure

01:39:30.860 --> 01:39:35.500
[Amit Varma]: is actually ubiquitous and in India inevitable because of the problems you pointed out, right?

01:39:35.500 --> 01:39:40.540
[Guest 1]: So our argument towards a presumptive laissez faire is very much in the Indian context,

01:39:40.540 --> 01:39:45.500
[Guest 1]: right? Because we regulate everything to death. So this is not saying that the government should

01:39:45.500 --> 01:39:51.020
[Guest 1]: not provide clean water, clean air should not have traffic signals or not solve air pollution,

01:39:51.020 --> 01:39:55.660
[Amit Varma]: those are the things that matter. Exactly. So you know, air pollution is a classic market

01:39:55.660 --> 01:39:59.580
[Guest 1]: externality, it is difficult to bring about collective action. So we need some good regulation

01:39:59.580 --> 01:40:04.060
[Guest 1]: to address that problem, right? So we're not saying that the government should not do any of

01:40:04.060 --> 01:40:08.700
[Guest 1]: that. In fact, we're saying the exact reverse. We're saying that for the government to be able

01:40:08.700 --> 01:40:13.180
[Guest 1]: to do that successfully, it should stop doing a lot of other things that it does,

01:40:13.740 --> 01:40:18.540
[Guest 1]: because of one of two reasons, either because that regulation is stupid and useless, which is

01:40:18.540 --> 01:40:22.940
[Guest 1]: most of our paternalist, you know, sort of redistributive regulation, which is anyway not

01:40:22.940 --> 01:40:29.260
[Guest 1]: followed. Or two, even if it's a good idea to have that regulation, it is too soon. And we cannot

01:40:29.260 --> 01:40:34.780
[Guest 1]: execute it well, we simply can't do it. So why not wait until India gets richer and has better

01:40:34.780 --> 01:40:41.020
[Guest 1]: state capacity, and then do those activities. So our focus on the night watchman state right with

01:40:41.020 --> 01:40:46.060
[Guest 1]: the presumptive laissez faire is not for an ideological reason, though that might also be

01:40:46.060 --> 01:40:51.500
[Guest 1]: true. But it's for a different reason, which is that we can't do more than the night watchman

01:40:51.500 --> 01:40:56.700
[Guest 1]: state with the current levels of Indian capacity. So we should really stop doing everything else

01:40:56.700 --> 01:41:01.260
[Guest 1]: and prioritize and at least get that done. So in a sense, we are libertarian by circumstance,

01:41:01.260 --> 01:41:05.340
[Guest 1]: not by belief. We should be by necessity. Yes, this is Kaushik Basu, right? India is full of

01:41:05.340 --> 01:41:09.660
[Guest 1]: libertarians by necessity, not libertarians by choice. I think there's a different problem with

01:41:09.660 --> 01:41:13.500
[Guest 2]: that. But we'll talk about that at another time. Exactly. And it's presumptive laissez faire,

01:41:13.500 --> 01:41:18.060
[Guest 2]: it's not necessarily laissez faire. You have to think about what we have now, which is presumptive

01:41:18.060 --> 01:41:23.660
[Guest 2]: statism. You know, the presumption among Indian policy elites is that they should have everything

01:41:23.660 --> 01:41:28.060
[Guest 2]: which the United States have. And there's two problems with that. One is the United States

01:41:28.060 --> 01:41:34.220
[Guest 2]: should have more laissez faire. That's problem number one. We're far too regulated in the U.S.,

01:41:34.220 --> 01:41:38.460
[Guest 2]: including many of the same problems and housing regulation and so forth. So that's problem number

01:41:38.460 --> 01:41:44.860
[Guest 2]: one. Problem number two is even if the U.S. had perfect regulation for a country of its GDP per

01:41:44.860 --> 01:41:52.540
[Guest 2]: capita, that does not translate into India, which has much lower GDP per capita. And it's not about,

01:41:52.540 --> 01:41:56.860
[Guest 2]: you know, the U.S. is great and India is not or something like that, because

01:41:56.860 --> 01:42:02.460
[Guest 2]: if the U.S. had lower GDP per capita, it should regulate less, too. And in fact,

01:42:02.460 --> 01:42:08.220
[Guest 2]: when the U.S. had lower GDP per capita, it did regulate a lot less. You could even argue that

01:42:08.220 --> 01:42:13.820
[Amit Varma]: some of that, you know, regulating less led to their higher GDP per capita. Absolutely. Absolutely.

01:42:13.820 --> 01:42:19.820
[Guest 2]: There may be a development path. And I think part of the problem is, is that people look around and

01:42:19.820 --> 01:42:26.300
[Guest 2]: they think, oh, we can skip the laissez faire period. We don't have to do what every other

01:42:26.300 --> 01:42:31.580
[Guest 2]: country did to become rich. So the countries which became rich all had kind of this laissez faire

01:42:31.580 --> 01:42:37.420
[Guest 2]: period, you know, Great Britain and the United States and Canada and so forth. And if you look

01:42:37.420 --> 01:42:42.780
[Guest 2]: around and you say, oh, well, we could just skip that and go straight to having, you know, middle

01:42:42.780 --> 01:42:48.940
[Guest 2]: of the road, mixed economy regulation, that I think is a mistake. There's a learning period.

01:42:48.940 --> 01:42:54.700
[Guest 2]: And laissez faire is part of the learning. You know, you need to get your police officers to

01:42:54.700 --> 01:43:01.580
[Guest 2]: be able to enforce a 50 rupee fine before they're able to enforce a 500 rupee fine.

01:43:01.580 --> 01:43:08.060
[Guest 2]: So first start small. That may be much better. And if you try and do the 500 rupee fine right away,

01:43:08.700 --> 01:43:13.180
[Guest 2]: then it's going to be subject to bribery. It's not going to work. Then the police officer is

01:43:13.180 --> 01:43:17.820
[Guest 2]: going to say, do you want the 500 rupee fine or do you want to pay me 100 now? And I'll forget

01:43:17.820 --> 01:43:25.020
[Guest 2]: about it. So that's the type of thing which when you entice the police officer with a possibility

01:43:25.020 --> 01:43:30.460
[Guest 2]: of having the income much higher than their wages, then you're naturally going to create a system of

01:43:30.460 --> 01:43:36.300
[Guest 2]: corruption. If instead you keep the fines low and just for, you know, the worst offenses,

01:43:36.940 --> 01:43:42.700
[Guest 2]: then the police officer is not tempted into corruption. So you need the whole laissez

01:43:42.700 --> 01:43:48.220
[Guest 2]: faire process is a learning process in which you develop state capacity.

01:43:48.220 --> 01:43:53.580
[Guest 1]: And the 500 rupee fine is also symptomatic of weak state capacity. What we've done is,

01:43:53.580 --> 01:43:59.820
[Guest 1]: as we know, right, there is a for any kind of punishment or any activity that one that the

01:43:59.820 --> 01:44:04.300
[Guest 1]: state wants one to avoid. There's the question of the probability of getting caught and the

01:44:04.300 --> 01:44:09.900
[Guest 1]: penalty of that particular action. Right now in India, we keep increasing the penalties

01:44:09.900 --> 01:44:14.300
[Guest 1]: because the probability of getting caught and prosecuted is very low. Right. And why is the

01:44:14.300 --> 01:44:18.380
[Guest 1]: probability of getting caught and prosecuted very low? Because we have very low state capacity.

01:44:18.380 --> 01:44:23.740
[Guest 1]: So we keep increasing the number of years of punishment, pretty much every activity from

01:44:23.740 --> 01:44:29.660
[Guest 1]: pulling the chain in a train, the emergency chain. Right. Everything has six months or more

01:44:29.660 --> 01:44:34.940
[Guest 1]: of imprisonment as a penalty. Everything has really high fines. So we are actually

01:44:34.940 --> 01:44:41.820
[Guest 1]: incentivizing all our state actors at the lower levels of governance to turn criminal because we

01:44:41.820 --> 01:44:47.980
[Guest 1]: haven't appropriately thought about how we optimize limited state capacity. And then when we

01:44:47.980 --> 01:44:53.180
[Guest 1]: substitute limited or weak state capacity with these other big fines, we have this huge problem,

01:44:53.180 --> 01:44:59.580
[Guest 1]: which is skipping the development step when it comes to state enforcement of basic things.

01:44:59.580 --> 01:45:05.820
[Guest 2]: And when you have a 50 rupee fine or a 10 rupee fine, that can be enforced pretty equally.

01:45:05.820 --> 01:45:09.740
[Guest 2]: When you have a 500 rupee fine, that is never going to be enforced equally at this stage.

01:45:09.740 --> 01:45:14.860
[Amit Varma]: Forget a 500 rupee fine where I live in Mumbai in the seven bungalows area, there is now

01:45:14.860 --> 01:45:19.900
[Amit Varma]: a new local fine that has come up, which is 20,000 rupees for cars which are parked wrongly.

01:45:19.900 --> 01:45:23.660
[Amit Varma]: The result, of course, is that no one I guarantee you will ever pay that fine.

01:45:23.660 --> 01:45:26.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but you know, but the rent seeking is great.

01:45:26.540 --> 01:45:30.700
[Amit Varma]: 20,000 rupees is a down payment for some of these cars. What are they talking about?

01:45:30.700 --> 01:45:34.860
[Amit Varma]: Ludicrous. It's some mad figure like that. I forget the exact number. It happened to a friend

01:45:34.860 --> 01:45:38.300
[Amit Varma]: and I was like, and she was like, oh, I paid a thousand buck bribe. Earlier,

01:45:38.300 --> 01:45:40.460
[Amit Varma]: it would have been a 200 buck bribe for her, you know.

01:45:41.260 --> 01:45:45.420
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so the only thing we're doing is we are making the system more corrupt

01:45:45.420 --> 01:45:46.460
[Amit Varma]: and more geared towards rent seeking.

01:45:46.460 --> 01:45:51.020
[Amit Varma]: And you're also incentivizing cops, look at these lucrative rent seeking opportunity

01:45:51.020 --> 01:45:54.940
[Amit Varma]: instead of doing the kind of policing you would actually like them to do.

01:45:54.940 --> 01:45:59.500
[Amit Varma]: So I have a couple of questions here. One is that I'm trying to imagine myself in a

01:45:59.500 --> 01:46:04.300
[Amit Varma]: policymaker's position where I have limited resources and even my own intellectual bandwidth

01:46:04.300 --> 01:46:10.860
[Amit Varma]: is limited. Now, given the complexity of the actual world, isn't this kind of elite imitation

01:46:10.860 --> 01:46:16.220
[Amit Varma]: rational, as designing something new from scratch will always, A, it will require me

01:46:16.220 --> 01:46:21.500
[Amit Varma]: to absorb a lot of local knowledge, two, it will bring its own set of unintended consequences.

01:46:21.500 --> 01:46:25.020
[Amit Varma]: And I can simply cover my ass by using a policy that

01:46:25.020 --> 01:46:28.700
[Amit Varma]: allows me to posture successfully that I'm doing something about the problem.

01:46:29.260 --> 01:46:35.180
[Guest 1]: Yes, I mean, it is rational in the sense that we respond to incentives. And as an academic or as

01:46:35.180 --> 01:46:40.140
[Guest 1]: an elite policymaker with the IAS, my best incentives might be to think about single

01:46:40.140 --> 01:46:44.540
[Guest 1]: use plastic ban because that'll get me invited to a nice conference, you know, speaking to

01:46:44.540 --> 01:46:48.780
[Guest 1]: other environmentalists who share my ideas and you know, things like that. So in that sense,

01:46:48.780 --> 01:46:53.820
[Guest 1]: it's rational that, you know, the means and ends are pretty, pretty tight, and it makes

01:46:53.820 --> 01:47:00.940
[Guest 1]: sense for them to do it. It is irrational, in that they are expecting completely different

01:47:00.940 --> 01:47:07.100
[Guest 1]: results, which have nothing to do with the logic of their actions, right? So expecting India to be

01:47:07.100 --> 01:47:12.220
[Guest 1]: open defecation free, because we distributed a bunch of toilets, that is completely irrational,

01:47:12.220 --> 01:47:17.020
[Guest 1]: because, you know, you can do it for your own personal reasons, but then don't expect

01:47:17.020 --> 01:47:20.140
[Guest 1]: the policy outcome. So that's what I would say about the...

01:47:20.140 --> 01:47:24.460
[Amit Varma]: But often there's a mismatch between the rewards that policymakers get in the actual policy

01:47:24.460 --> 01:47:28.220
[Amit Varma]: outcomes, right? Because a policy outcome may happen years down the line, they've moved on

01:47:28.220 --> 01:47:32.860
[Amit Varma]: to some other department, you know, yesterday's education secretary will be tomorrow's transport

01:47:32.860 --> 01:47:37.740
[Amit Varma]: secretary. So, you know, why not just do the safe thing, not do anything drastic,

01:47:37.740 --> 01:47:42.220
[Amit Varma]: take the least effort possible, and you can posture and get invited to conferences.

01:47:42.220 --> 01:47:46.780
[Guest 1]: Yes, and no. You know, when I meet IAS officers, they also tend to deeply care.

01:47:46.780 --> 01:47:51.180
[Guest 1]: Now, we have to remember, these are career civil servants, right? They've gone from department to

01:47:51.180 --> 01:47:54.860
[Guest 1]: department looking at different kinds of problems. They've served at the district magistrate level,

01:47:54.860 --> 01:47:59.420
[Guest 1]: they've seen some of the ground reality, even though a very, very long time ago,

01:47:59.420 --> 01:48:05.660
[Guest 1]: it might not be the relevant reality of today. But they really seem to care that policies that

01:48:05.660 --> 01:48:11.660
[Guest 1]: they work on do have the intended result. And I also see a lot of frustration among elites

01:48:11.660 --> 01:48:17.340
[Guest 1]: Indian policymakers, when the policies that they do care about don't have the intended outcome,

01:48:17.340 --> 01:48:22.780
[Guest 1]: right? So, I would ascribe the best of public spirited intentions to them,

01:48:22.780 --> 01:48:25.820
[Guest 1]: and say that we still have this problem of elite imitation.

01:48:25.820 --> 01:48:30.540
[Amit Varma]: No, and actually, our government services filled with talented, really smart, well meaning people,

01:48:30.540 --> 01:48:34.860
[Amit Varma]: I have to tell you this, I was we are recording this on Feb 10, I was at the Witherba Lit Fest

01:48:35.740 --> 01:48:40.700
[Amit Varma]: yesterday in Nagpur, and there's an income tax training academy there. And a couple of students

01:48:40.700 --> 01:48:45.420
[Amit Varma]: from that academy came and they asked me some great questions, quoting from my episodes. And

01:48:45.420 --> 01:48:49.100
[Amit Varma]: then finally, they said they were big fans, and they made me sign on a piece of paper,

01:48:49.100 --> 01:48:50.780
[Amit Varma]: the words taxation is theft.

01:48:51.340 --> 01:48:53.340
[Guest 1]: Please don't name them and get them fired.

01:48:53.340 --> 01:48:58.380
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely not. Indoctrinate the deep state. Now, my final question actually moves away.

01:48:58.380 --> 01:49:03.660
[Guest 2]: Let me just answer a brief point on that issue. And that is this, you know, in many places in the

01:49:03.660 --> 01:49:11.100
[Guest 2]: world, in the US and places in particular, we have a not invented here mindset, which means that if

01:49:11.100 --> 01:49:17.580
[Guest 2]: it wasn't invented here, it must be no good. But actually, India often has my experiences, if it

01:49:17.580 --> 01:49:25.340
[Guest 2]: was not invented here, if it was invented here, it's no good. And often, I think India tries to

01:49:25.340 --> 01:49:31.980
[Guest 2]: import too much, a little bit of a invented here is good would be I think, a pro mindset.

01:49:31.980 --> 01:49:36.700
[Amit Varma]: No, and there's a little bit of like, for example, the free rider effect there in the sense that why

01:49:36.700 --> 01:49:41.340
[Amit Varma]: do all the hard work and research, why not free ride on the sort of findings of others?

01:49:41.340 --> 01:49:45.740
[Guest 1]: Oh, yeah, free riding reminds me of something fantastic I read in Ajay Shah's book,

01:49:45.740 --> 01:49:51.340
[Guest 1]: and Vijay Kelkar's book, and we had a chat about it. And one of the points that they discuss is

01:49:51.340 --> 01:49:57.580
[Guest 1]: to relieve certain areas of Indian state capacity to do other things better, India should just free

01:49:57.580 --> 01:50:03.500
[Guest 1]: ride on the regulatory capacity of other countries. So if something is FDA approved, India should just

01:50:03.500 --> 01:50:07.980
[Amit Varma]: adopt it. No other questions asked. Because they overregulate madly. So if they've approved it,

01:50:07.980 --> 01:50:13.020
[Guest 1]: it's fine. Exactly. So they overregulate, you know, maybe it's not optimal, or, you know,

01:50:13.020 --> 01:50:17.500
[Guest 1]: efficient in the market sense. But it's efficient for India to adopt it because it frees up an

01:50:17.500 --> 01:50:22.540
[Guest 1]: enormous amount of food safety regulation in you know, in terms of how much of the budget goes

01:50:22.540 --> 01:50:27.020
[Guest 1]: towards it, in terms of how many officers are employed towards it. So according to me, and even

01:50:27.020 --> 01:50:33.020
[Guest 1]: I wrote about this, I think state capacity freed is state capacity built. Right. So in that sense,

01:50:33.020 --> 01:50:38.620
[Guest 1]: any area where we can free ride on state capacity of first world, Alex has made a similar argument

01:50:38.620 --> 01:50:45.420
[Guest 1]: on visas, where he says that, you know, if 182 countries can go to Germany without a visa,

01:50:45.420 --> 01:50:50.380
[Guest 1]: it should be good enough for India, right? What's the problem? So you just let them come to India,

01:50:50.380 --> 01:50:55.020
[Guest 1]: same as before. Now you can have additional visa requirements if someone needs a work permit or

01:50:55.020 --> 01:50:59.340
[Guest 1]: longer stays and things like that, or, you know, to move towards permanent residency, and so on,

01:50:59.340 --> 01:51:07.500
[Guest 1]: so forth. But just to visit India, the kind of requirements you have, you must fulfill to get

01:51:07.500 --> 01:51:14.300
[Guest 1]: the visa is quite annoying. And the typical first world rich elite traveler couldn't be bothered

01:51:14.300 --> 01:51:20.220
[Guest 1]: with filling forms in triplicate and providing the birthplace of mother and father, you know,

01:51:20.220 --> 01:51:24.620
[Guest 1]: bank statements and all of those things. If they have an American or Canadian or German or you

01:51:24.620 --> 01:51:31.340
[Guest 1]: know, any one of those 180 passports should be good for us. And that will really boost tourism.

01:51:31.340 --> 01:51:36.780
[Guest 1]: So in the in this sense, we could actually free up a lot of Indian state capacity by free riding.

01:51:37.500 --> 01:51:41.100
[Amit Varma]: Right, and you have five minutes left, because you have to take a metro to Noida before you

01:51:41.100 --> 01:51:46.940
[Amit Varma]: catch a flight later in the evening. So not so elite after all, but however, catching a flight

01:51:46.940 --> 01:51:51.340
[Amit Varma]: later in the evening to back to the US. So very, very, very elite. I mean, two hours is like way

01:51:51.340 --> 01:51:55.820
[Amit Varma]: too short for a podcast, I almost feel like what it's only good for soundbites. But there was one

01:51:55.820 --> 01:52:00.620
[Amit Varma]: thing I would have asked you to elaborate on a little longer. And I will quickly ask your comments

01:52:00.620 --> 01:52:05.820
[Amit Varma]: on that, which is since you're an expert on it, on that subject called the Constitution, that,

01:52:05.820 --> 01:52:08.620
[Amit Varma]: you know, what's the Constitution and example of elite imitation?

01:52:09.500 --> 01:52:17.740
[Guest 1]: Ah, yes and no. To some extent it is, because until then, all the constitutions were not written

01:52:17.740 --> 01:52:23.420
[Guest 1]: for a context like India, right? So India is not a country subcontinent had enormous amount of

01:52:23.420 --> 01:52:29.020
[Guest 1]: ethnic, caste and linguistic fractionalization. But we try to bring it under one umbrella.

01:52:29.020 --> 01:52:36.620
[Guest 1]: And we try to, as far as possible, create systems, right, like a parliamentary system,

01:52:36.620 --> 01:52:41.500
[Guest 1]: separation of powers, you know, judicial review, these are just systems that were in some sense

01:52:41.500 --> 01:52:47.580
[Guest 1]: alien to India, right? So we created, you know, the idea of checks and balances of three different

01:52:47.580 --> 01:52:51.900
[Guest 1]: branches of government, Westminster procedure, when it comes to parliamentary procedure,

01:52:51.900 --> 01:52:59.340
[Guest 1]: all of this in some sense is colonial heritage or elite imitation, right? But the constitutional

01:52:59.340 --> 01:53:05.660
[Guest 1]: framers were not just elites, right? They represented pretty much every aspect of Indian

01:53:05.660 --> 01:53:09.340
[Guest 1]: life, though not in the proportions that I think were ideal, right? They weren't a perfect

01:53:09.340 --> 01:53:14.940
[Guest 1]: representation in terms of the census. But they had all kinds of representation in terms of

01:53:14.940 --> 01:53:19.820
[Guest 1]: different ideologies, like you had people from Hindu Mahasabha, you also had people who were,

01:53:19.820 --> 01:53:25.500
[Guest 1]: you know, atheist communists, right? So Indian, if you look at the oath to take office in India,

01:53:25.500 --> 01:53:30.540
[Guest 1]: an atheist can also take the oath of office to any government position, because you don't have

01:53:30.540 --> 01:53:36.300
[Guest 1]: to take the oath to whatever God you believe in, right? That's a really odd thing about Indian

01:53:36.300 --> 01:53:40.460
[Amit Varma]: constitutional framing. This is music to my ears as an atheist. But also, I don't believe in the

01:53:40.460 --> 01:53:45.340
[Amit Varma]: false religion of government. So I don't think I would be taking that oath. But fair enough.

01:53:45.340 --> 01:53:52.300
[Guest 2]: But some elite imitation can be good. And I admire most about, you know, the Indian founders and

01:53:52.300 --> 01:53:59.820
[Guest 2]: Nehru and Bekar and Gandhi is they did imitate, you know, free speech issues, the secularism,

01:53:59.820 --> 01:54:06.780
[Guest 2]: openness to all religions, and so forth. It's very, very, very impressive. And that is something

01:54:06.780 --> 01:54:10.300
[Amit Varma]: which I think they got right. I mean, you could even argue that in some cases, elite imitation

01:54:10.300 --> 01:54:15.420
[Amit Varma]: is required, because the argument would be that we were and are in many ways a very illiberal

01:54:15.420 --> 01:54:21.820
[Amit Varma]: society, then and the Constitution by imposing that kind of liberalism, paradoxically, might

01:54:21.820 --> 01:54:27.740
[Amit Varma]: also play a part in, ironically, in allowing that illiberalism to gain political dominance,

01:54:27.740 --> 01:54:32.300
[Guest 1]: but that's a different matter. I have something to add here, there was elite imitation,

01:54:32.300 --> 01:54:37.500
[Guest 1]: but the elites of the time did not sound and look like the elites of today. Right? All the people

01:54:37.500 --> 01:54:42.540
[Guest 1]: were talking about Gandhi, Nehru, Ambedkar, they spoke multiple languages. They read and wrote in

01:54:42.540 --> 01:54:48.780
[Guest 1]: their regional language. In fact, the Constituent Assembly debates are mind blowing. In the sort of

01:54:48.780 --> 01:54:54.780
[Guest 1]: diversity. So Ambedkar might have made fantastic speeches in English, but he also spoke Gujarati

01:54:54.780 --> 01:54:59.900
[Guest 1]: and he could also convey everything he wanted to convey in Gujarati pretty much at the same if not

01:54:59.900 --> 01:55:07.100
[Guest 1]: a higher standard of eloquence, right? Same with Gandhi, right? Nehru was excellent in Hindi. So

01:55:07.100 --> 01:55:14.140
[Guest 1]: this is not today's Indian elite, right? So today's Indian elite is not speaking and communicating in

01:55:14.140 --> 01:55:18.700
[Guest 1]: three different languages. They did not grow up, they don't go back to their ancestral village,

01:55:18.700 --> 01:55:23.020
[Guest 1]: you know, so on and so forth. So I do want to say that even though there was elite imitation,

01:55:23.020 --> 01:55:29.580
[Guest 1]: the Indian constitutional framers were deeply rooted in Indian culture, right? They had been

01:55:29.580 --> 01:55:34.220
[Guest 1]: through the beats of the Indian system. Now, yes, Gandhi didn't live in a village. And you know,

01:55:34.220 --> 01:55:39.180
[Guest 1]: he grew up in cities, Ambedkar had more village experience. So you might have diversity like that.

01:55:39.180 --> 01:55:44.300
[Guest 1]: You also had princes and kings, right, who had spent their summers, you know, hanging out in

01:55:44.300 --> 01:55:49.820
[Guest 1]: London, and who had been to Eton and, you know, well versed with the British liberal tradition

01:55:49.820 --> 01:55:55.900
[Guest 1]: and the Magna Carta. So you have all sorts of people. But you also have people from backward

01:55:55.900 --> 01:56:01.580
[Guest 1]: castes, right? You also have tribal representation, though as not in as many, like not the numbers that

01:56:01.580 --> 01:56:06.540
[Guest 1]: one would like. So the Indian constitutional framers might have been the elites of their time.

01:56:06.540 --> 01:56:13.740
[Guest 1]: But the elites of our time are not a patch on them, right? So just in terms of lived experience,

01:56:13.740 --> 01:56:18.060
[Guest 1]: language, and how rooted they were in Indian culture, so they only borrowed the very best,

01:56:18.060 --> 01:56:23.580
[Guest 1]: and they knew how to distinguish that. But at the same time, I mean, everyone does

01:56:23.580 --> 01:56:28.300
[Guest 1]: what they can do. The only thing I would say to the Indian elites of today, and I would include

01:56:28.300 --> 01:56:35.420
[Guest 1]: myself in this category, is we need to pay more attention to who the median Indian is.

01:56:35.420 --> 01:56:40.380
[Amit Varma]: And we need in general, more intellectual humility, I think. Alex, let me end by asking you

01:56:40.380 --> 01:56:45.420
[Amit Varma]: the last question, which is that you're someone who has spent a fair amount of time in India.

01:56:45.420 --> 01:56:49.660
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, you spent a few months in Mumbai, when we last recorded the episodes we did. Now,

01:56:49.660 --> 01:56:54.620
[Amit Varma]: you've been here for a while teaching a course on public choice theory. What is it about the

01:56:54.620 --> 01:56:59.420
[Amit Varma]: Indian policy environment or the Indian economic environment that sort of excites you? Which is,

01:56:59.420 --> 01:57:04.460
[Amit Varma]: you know, what is exciting about it? What is scary about it? Looking from the outside and also from

01:57:04.460 --> 01:57:09.660
[Amit Varma]: the inside, in a sense that what has been happening over the last few years? What gives you hope and

01:57:09.660 --> 01:57:14.540
[Guest 2]: what gives you despair? So I think what's interesting and exciting about India is that

01:57:14.540 --> 01:57:20.780
[Guest 2]: many decisions are being made today, which are going to influence future generations. India has,

01:57:20.780 --> 01:57:27.020
[Guest 2]: you know, multiple paths, and which path is taken today? Think about urbanization. When you lay down

01:57:27.020 --> 01:57:33.340
[Guest 2]: the bones of a city, those byways, they will remain there for the next hundreds of years.

01:57:33.340 --> 01:57:38.940
[Guest 2]: You know, like London today, you can still see London from hundreds of years ago. So these

01:57:38.940 --> 01:57:45.580
[Guest 2]: decisions, you only urbanize once, okay? A country only urbanizes once. And we're seeing that in

01:57:45.580 --> 01:57:51.180
[Guest 2]: India today. We're seeing lots and lots of policy decisions, which can have a tremendous influence

01:57:51.180 --> 01:57:57.260
[Guest 2]: on millions and millions of people's lives. So I think India is an amazing place to think about

01:57:57.260 --> 01:58:03.260
[Guest 2]: policy, because there's so many possibilities which are open to it. The United States,

01:58:03.260 --> 01:58:09.900
[Guest 2]: in contrast, is fixed. It's like the Titanic, or like an oil tanker. Maybe it's the Titanic,

01:58:09.900 --> 01:58:14.060
[Guest 2]: we don't know yet. But whether it's an oil tanker or the Titanic, it's hard to move,

01:58:14.060 --> 01:58:19.420
[Guest 2]: it's hard to change. Well, so many more possibilities seem open to India. India can

01:58:19.420 --> 01:58:25.020
[Guest 2]: be so much different, so much more. And that this is happening now, I think makes India very exciting

01:58:25.020 --> 01:58:29.900
[Amit Varma]: to a person interested in policy. You just lifted my mood up with that note of hope.

01:58:29.900 --> 01:58:35.180
[Amit Varma]: Guys, thanks so much for coming on the show. Great to be here. Thank you.

01:58:59.900 --> 01:59:01.180
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for listening.

